</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02E</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Warrington CCG</p></td><td><p>694</p></td><td><p>3,250</p></td><td><p>3,265</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02F</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS West Cheshire CCG</p></td><td><p>4,803</p></td><td><p>4,350</p></td><td><p>4,515</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02G</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS West Lancashire CCG</p></td><td><p>1,454</p></td><td><p>1,635</p></td><td><p>2,155</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02H</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Wigan Borough CCG</p></td><td><p>3,536</p></td><td><p>6,020</p></td><td><p>3,990</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>02M</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Fylde and Wyre CCG</p></td><td><p>1,534</p></td><td><p>1,510</p></td><td><p>2,550</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>12F</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Wirral CCG</p></td><td><p>3,323</p></td><td><p>4,080</p></td><td><p>5,410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>99A</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Liverpool CCG</p></td><td><p>6,684</p></td><td><p>8,115</p></td><td><p>9,420</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>99C</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS North Tyneside CCG</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>5,015</p></td><td><p>3,810</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p><em>Data source</em>: IAPT, Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC)</p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p>1. A referral is classified as having entered treatment if it has a first, attended treatment appointment in the year.</p><p>2. For 2012-13, referrals entering treatment is a subset of referrals received in the year, as this was the first year of the IAPT programme.</p><p>3. For 2014-15, CCG is the recorded commissioner, unless this was not recorded or not a CCG, in which case the CCG is derived from the patient’s general practitioner (GP) practice or postcode. For 2013-14 and 2012-13, CCG is based on GP Practice. Where CCG and GP Practice were not recorded and could not be assigned, the referral is categorised as 'Unknown'. A list of valid CCGs can be found on the HSCIC website at:</p><p><a href="http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/othernhs" target="_blank">http://systems.hscic.gov.uk/data/ods/datadownloads/othernhs</a></p><p>4. For this response, we are defining North West and East Lancashire as those CCGs within the following NHS Health Authority regions: Q74 - NHS England North (Cumbria and North East), Q75 - NHS England North (Cheshire and Merseyside), Q83 - NHS England North (Greater Manchester), Q84 - NHS England North (Lancashire).</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-26T09:00:20.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539616/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539616/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have entered the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Programme in (a) England, (b) the North West and (c) East Lancashire in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","43089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539617","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>It is for Health Education England (HEE) to determine how it consults with partners in the development of its workforce plan. The Care Act 2014 requires HEE to obtain advice on the delivery of its functions from a wide range of people, including those involved in the delivery of education and training. In developing its previous workforce plans, HEE has consulted with professional bodies and other stakeholders and has considered the evidence that they have made available.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T13:18:45.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539617/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539617/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Health Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will consult professional bodies to determine workforce requirements prior to the publication of Health Education England's Workforce Plan for England.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","43067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539618","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has developed Fingertips, a rich source of indicators across a range of health and wellbeing themes that have been designed to support the Joint Strategic Needs Assessment and commissioning to improve health and wellbeing and reduce inequalities. The sexual and reproductive health profiles for local authorities can be found in the following link:</p><p><a href="http://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/sexualhealth/data#page/9/gid/8000057/pat/6/par/E12000004/ati/101/are/E06000015" target="_blank">http://fingertips.phe.org.uk/profile/sexualhealth/data#page/9/gid/8000057/pat/6/par/E12000004/ati/101/are/E06000015</a></p><p> </p><p>Data at parliamentary constituency level is not available for any measure as requested.</p><p> </p><p>It is estimated that for 2014 (the most recent year for which figures are available) there are 103,700 people living with HIV (includes both diagnosed and undiagnosed infection) in the United Kingdom; a breakdown for England only is not available. Further breakdown by local authority is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 below shows the number of people newly diagnosed with HIV, numbers of death in people with HIV, number people accessing HIV care and HIV testing in England and proportion of adults diagnosed with a cluster of differentiation 4 (CD4) count below 350 cells, for 2014.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>England</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>New HIV diagnoses (all ages)</p></td><td><p>5,559</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deaths in people with HIV (all ages)</p></td><td><p>518</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Accessing HIV care (all ages)</p></td><td><p>78,317</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HIV tests performed in sexual health clinics (all ages) (2015)</p></td><td><p>1,129,456</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HIV self-sampling service (all ages) (November 2015 – July 2016 only)</p></td><td><p>15,631</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HIV tests performed in antenatal settings (all ages)</p></td><td><p>693,570</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proportion of people with CD4 count below 350 cells within 91 days of diagnosis (all ages)</p></td><td><p>40% (1,748/4415)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note:</p><p> </p><p>I. Data is not included on additional HIV tests undertaken in England such as on blood donors, tests conducted by general practitioners that are not on pregnant women, tests undertaken by private practitioners or pharmacies, etc.</p><p>II. New HIV diagnoses are not synonymous with new HIV infections; people can and do live with an undiagnosed HIV infection for many years before they are diagnosed.</p><p>III. The proportion of people diagnosed with a CD4 count.</p><p>IV. Numbers accessing care at the local authority level are restricted to age groups 15-59 years to be consistent with British HIV Association HIV testing guidelines.</p><p>V. Data on HIV testing in sexual health clinics represent the total number of HIV tests performed and not the number of people tested for HIV. HIV testing data exclude people accessing sexual health clinics located in England who are residents in Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland or abroad.</p><p>VI. The figure presented for the HIV self-sampling service represents the total number of kits returned for testing and are provisional. Data are available from November 2015, when the service began to mid July 2016. Data presented are for period November 2015 to January 2016 available from conference presentation by Guerra e<em>t al</em> 0O38:</p><p><a href="http://www.bashh.org/documents/Events/Conference%202016/BASHH%20Conference%202016%20Abstract%20Book.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.bashh.org/documents/Events/Conference%202016/BASHH%20Conference%202016%20Abstract%20Book.pdf</a></p><p>Local Authority data are owned by local commissioners and not published nationally.</p><p>VII. Deaths include all-cause mortality, including non-HIV related deaths.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","43054 ; 43055 ; 43078 ; 43079","2016-07-25T16:18:17.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539618/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539618/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the proportion of adults with HIV that had a CD4 cell count below 350 within 91 days of diagnosis in (a) England, (b) each parliamentary constituency and (c) each local authority area in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","43080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539619","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>The provision of local health services is a matter for the local National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>The Lancashire Children and Young People’s Resilience, Emotional Wellbeing and Mental Health Transformation Plan 2015-2020 sets out plans for improvements to services, including eating disorder services. The Plan can be accessed using the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.blackburnwithdarwenccg.nhs.uk/health/child-health/camhs/" target="_blank">http://www.blackburnwithdarwenccg.nhs.uk/health/child-health/camhs/</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-25T16:12:59.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539619/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539619/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Eating Disorders: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve community-based eating disorder services in East Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","43081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539620","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>For the first time, there is now a publication of a national workforce plan for England setting out the investment that will be made in the education and training of the workforce. In developing the plan, Health Education England (HEE) has worked closely with local National Health Service providers, commissioners and other partners to ensure that it reflects the future workforce that is needed to deliver health services.</p><p>HEE has published three workforce plans to date, in December 2013, December 2014 and most recently in May 2016. The latest plan sets out the education commissions that HEE will make in 2016/17. The latest Workforce plan can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.hee.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/documents/HEE%20Workforce%20Plan%20for%20England%202016%20180516_0.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.hee.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/documents/HEE%20Workforce%20Plan%20for%20England%202016%20180516_0.pdf</a></p><p>HEE is working with partners to strengthen local arrangements for workforce planning for example, it is establishing Local Workforce Action Boards which will be aligned to Sustainability and Transformation Plan geographies, thereby ensuring that workforce will be at the heart of decision making and implementation of future service transformation.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T14:41:33.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539620/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539620/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the devolution of NHS workforce planning.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","43180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539621","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>The independent review into health inequalities in England undertaken by Professor Sir Michael Marmot culminated in the publication in 2010 of Fair Society, Healthy Lives. The review identified the most effective evidence-based strategies for reducing health inequalities in England and made the following recommendation:</p><p> </p><p>“Tobacco control is central to any strategy to tackle health inequalities as smoking accounts for approximately half of the difference in life expectancy between the lowest and highest income groups. Smoking-related death rates are two to three times higher in low-income groups than in wealthier social groups.”</p><p> </p><p>The new tobacco control plan is currently being developed and Ministers will decide on an appropriate publication date in due course.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-25T16:19:17.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539621/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Smoking: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what data exists about the proportion of excess mortality in lower socioeconomic status groups due to smoking-related diseases; whether the forthcoming tobacco control strategy for England will contain measures to address that issue; and when he expects to publish the next tobacco control strategy for England.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","43155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539622","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>It is the primary responsibility of commissioners to ensure continuity of commissioned services through contracting and contingency planning. Where a provider is considered hard to replace in the event of failure, its services can be designated as Commissioner Requested Services. This requires the provider to obtain a provider licence, if not otherwise required to hold a licence, and places the provider in NHS Improvement’s financial oversight regime for private providers of essential NHS services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","43130","2016-07-21T13:10:46.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539622/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539622/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what procedures are in place to safeguard patient transport services if a private provider of such a service goes into administration.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539623","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department does not hold this information. The National Health Service body commissioning a service from the private sector should ensure that adequate safeguards are in place to ensure access to essential operational equipment in the event of one of its suppliers getting into financial difficulties.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T13:08:04.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539623/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539623/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of occasions on which bailiffs have seized operational equipment from private providers of NHS services; what the details are of each such occasion; and what steps his Department takes to prevent this happening.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539624","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>It is the primary responsibility of commissioners to ensure continuity of commissioned services through contracting and contingency planning. Where a provider is considered hard to replace in the event of failure, its services can be designated as Commissioner Requested Services. This requires the provider to obtain a provider licence, if not otherwise required to hold a licence, and places the provider in NHS Improvement’s financial oversight regime for private providers of essential NHS services.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","43127","2016-07-21T13:10:46.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539624/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539624/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on NHS services of private providers of those services entering into administration or suffering serious financial difficulty; and what contingency provisions he has put in place to mitigate such effects.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539625","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>This is a matter for local commissioners.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has confirmed that Coperforma, holder of the non-emergency Patient Transport Service (PTS) contract for Sussex, informed High Weald Lewes Havens Clinical Commissioning Group (HWLH CCG) on 16 June 2016 that a receiver had been appointed for VM Langfords - transport provider sub-contracted to deliver PTS in East and West Sussex. A number of South East Coast Ambulance Services (SECAmb) staff had been transferred to VM Langfords employment.</p><p> </p><p>HWLH CCG met with Coperforma on 17 June 2016 and was assured that a plan was already in place for additional transport capacity to mitigate any loss of capacity that this situation may cause.</p><p> </p><p>HWLH CCG is working closely with Coperforma and the unions (Unison and GMB) to work through the implications for ex SECAmb staff, to ensure the processes followed are in keeping with employment legislation and good practice and that the impacts on service delivery are kept to a minimum.</p><p> </p><p>There have been no discussions between Ministers in the Department and Sussex CCGs about PTS provider VM Langfords going into administration.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","42969","2016-07-21T07:50:52.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539625/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539625/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions Ministers in his Department have had with Sussex clinical commissioning groups about patient transport service provider Langfords going into administration.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539626","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department is committed to improving diagnosis and management of sepsis and has a wide programme of work underway. We will consider the German Ministry of Health’s draft resolution to the World Health Assembly in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T14:40:45.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539626/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539626/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Sepsis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to support the Department of International and European Affairs of the German Ministry of Health's draft resolution on sepsis for the World Health Assembly General Assembly meeting in 2017.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","43224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539627","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>NHS England has published all of the recommendations made by the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) which relate to interventions in the Cancer Programme of Care, listed in Appendix 3 of NHS England's paper on <em>Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP)-HIV Prevention</em>.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of recommendations were published in June 2016, except those that CPAG had already considered (as in-year service developments) in early 2016. This includes policies relating to chemotherapy drugs and everolimus to treat angiomyolipomas, which were included in the PrEP paper in error.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-21T08:19:07.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539627/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539627/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England published all of the recommendations made in June 2016 by its Clinical Priorities Advisory Group relating to the medical interventions in the Cancer Programme of Care listed in Appendix 3 of NHS England's paper on Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP)-HIV Prevention, published in May 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539628","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. Such information as is available is attached.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England publishes information on the number of attendances at all types of accident and emergency department. A type 3 accident and emergency department is one that treats minor injuries and illnesses (sprains for example) and can be routinely accessed without an appointment. In this context, minor ailments have been interpreted as a type 3 accident and emergency attendance.</p><p> </p><p>Data are reported to NHS England by all organisations providing National Health Service funded emergency care services and averaging more than 200 attendees per month. It is not possible to aggregate these data to clinical commissioning group, and the 10 strategic health authorities were abolished in March 2013. Published data for type 3 attendances are only available from 2011-12 onwards. These data are presented by 13 commissioning sub-regions, which are not legal entities but are sub-divisions of NHS England.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","43137","2016-07-21T15:16:06.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539628/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539628/answer","PQ43137 - DATA.xlsx","PQ43137 PQ43137 data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539628/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of visits to accident and emergency departments were for minor ailments in (a) England and (b) former strategic health authority areas in each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539629","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>Hospital Episode Statistics (HES) provide information on the number of miscarriages. The table shows the number of miscarriages from 2010/11 to 2014/15 where there was a hospital admission.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of miscarriages</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>43,005</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>42,538</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>39,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>38,869</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>38,377</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Activity in English National Health Service hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector</p><p> </p><p>Source: HES, Health and Social Care Information Centre</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T15:17:31.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539629/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539629/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Miscarriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many women in each of the last five years had a miscarriage.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539630","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>According to a report prepared for the Department and published by Frontier Economics in October 2014, unsafe care can cost the National Health Service between £1 billion and £2.5 billion a year.</p><p> </p><p>In order to improve the safety of patients, we have established various initiatives including:</p><p> </p><p>- The Sign up to Safety Campaign officially launched in June 2014. More than 390 organisations have signed up thus far, and we are aware of more than 670 projects to reduce avoidable harm. Organisations that sign up must outline what they will do to strengthen patient safety, including a response to five key pledges and a safety improvement plan that demonstrates how they intend to save lives/reduce harm over the next three years. The campaign aims to help member organisations listen to patients, carers and staff, learn from what they say when things go wrong and take action to improve patient’s safety, helping to ensure patients get harm free care every time, everywhere;</p><p> </p><p>- The Patient Safety Collaboratives, a programme to improve the safety of patients and ensure that continual patient safety learning sits at the heart of healthcare in England; and</p><p> </p><p>- The NHS Safety Thermometer, a measurement tool for a programme of work to support patient safety improvement.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T14:35:56.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539630/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539630/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the financial cost of incidences of human error within the NHS; and what steps his Department has taken to reduce the likelihood of such errors.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","43153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539631","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>This information is not collected.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:52:55.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539631/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539631/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Headaches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in each of the last five years were diagnosed with cluster headaches.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539632","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>General practitioners can prescribe any product, which they consider to be a medicine necessary for the treatment of their patients providing that the product is not included in Schedules 1 or 2 to the NHS (General Medical Services contracts) (Prescription of Drugs etc.) Regulations 2004 and the doctor is prepared to justify any challenges to their prescribing by their local primary care organisation.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-26T14:43:52.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539632/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539632/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Osteoporosis: Dietary Supplements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to make dietary supplements to address osteoporosis available through the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539633","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>There is no plan to change the way that the National Health Service is funded nor any consideration of changes. The Government remains committed to the principles of the NHS, enshrined in the NHS Constitution, that access to NHS services is based on clinical need, not the ability to pay.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also committed to working with the NHS in implementing its own plan for the future of the NHS – the Five Year Forward View – backed up by the commitment made in the Spending Review to provide an additional £10 billion in real terms by 2020-21 compared to 2014-15. This fully funds the plan.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","43034","2016-07-21T14:39:16.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539633/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539633/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has any plans to move away from a tax-funded NHS towards one funded by insurance and co-payments.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","43154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539634","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>Butter is high in saturated fat. Evidence shows that average population intakes of saturated fat exceed United Kingdom government advice which is to limit saturated fat intake to no more than 11% of total food energy to protect against heart disease.</p><p> </p><p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition is currently reviewing the evidence on saturated fat and health; it aims to publish a draft report at the end of 2017.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-20T14:19:36.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539634/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539634/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Heart Diseases: Butter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of whether eating butter puts people at greater risk of heart disease.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539635","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Department advises National Health Service bodies that they must comply with the Procurement Contracts Regulations (PCR) 2015. Regulation 71 requires the prime contractor to provide the contracting authority with names and contact details of personnel in the supply chain. Additionally, regulation 113 requires a contracting authority to place an obligation on the prime contractor to pay undisputed invoices in 30 days down the supply chain.</p><p>The Crown Commercial Service has published guidance on paying undisputed invoices in 30 days. The following link takes you to the Crown Commercial Service guidance:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/524355/Paying_undispute_invoices_within_30_days_in_supply_chain.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/524355/Paying_undispute_invoices_within_30_days_in_supply_chain.pdf</a></p><p>The Department has developed standard NHS terms and conditions for use by NHS bodies procuring non-clinical goods and services from commercial suppliers. Clause 9 ‘Price and payment’ places an obligation on the prime contractor to pay undisputed invoices to its sub-contractors within a period not exceeding 30 days. Clause 28 ‘Assignment, novation and subcontracting’ covers 30 day payment terms for sub-contractors. This clause also states the prime supplier shall endeavour to pay its relevant sub-contractors within a comparable timeframe from receipt by the supplier of such undisputed invoices from its sub-contractors. The following link takes you to the full suite of the NHS Terms and Conditions including the overarching guidance note:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nhs-standard-terms-and-conditions-of-contract-for-the-purchase-of-goods-and-supply-of-services" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/nhs-standard-terms-and-conditions-of-contract-for-the-purchase-of-goods-and-supply-of-services</a></p><p>Additionally, NHS England mandates that any clinical services commissioned by clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are on the terms of the NHS Standard Contract, which prohibits sub-contracting without the prior written consent of the CCG. The CCG may require approval of the form of sub-contract used, but NHS England does not and cannot itself prescribe the form of sub-contract (although it does publish a template which the CCG may require its provider to use when sub-contracting). Notwithstanding any sub-contracting, the commissioned provider remains responsible to the CCG for delivery of the service.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-26T14:45:22.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539635/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539635/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","NHS: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what requirements his Department directs NHS organisations to place on direct contractors who sub-contract to other providers.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539636","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>It is for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to satisfy themselves of the financial viability of any provider of patient transport, or of any other service, to which it intends to award a contract.</p><p> </p><p>It is for CCGs to determine how best to meet their statutory functions and duties and their standing financial instructions.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:56:39.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539636/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539636/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what financial checks clinical commissioning groups are required to make on companies which tender contracts for patient transport services in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539637","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Lower acuity calls, such as minor ailments, are called “green calls”. Response times for these are set locally by commissioners and providers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T13:06:30.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539637/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539637/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of ambulance call-outs were for minor ailments in each (a) former strategic health authority area and (b) clinical commissioning group in each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539638","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>Initial analysis of the potential financial impact of self-care interventions demonstrated that there is the ability for a substantial amount of savings to be derived from the Self-care Programme over the next few years. This is subject to the successful delivery of alternative, complementary programmes of activity over the same period.</p><p><br> NHS England is in the process of conducting detailed financial modelling predicated on a suite of self-care interventions distributed across five evidence-based areas of practice identified through the Realising the Value Programme. This detailed modelling will result in the production of a number of toolkits for commissioners due to be published this autumn. More information can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.nesta.org.uk/project/realising-value" target="_blank"><br> www.nesta.org.uk/project/realising-value</a></p><p> </p><p>In terms of potential savings that each clinical commissioning group (CCG) could make through greater promotion of self-care for patients, each CCG will start from a different point in terms of the amount and quality of self-care that its population currently undertakes and will also have different future potential in scope for self-care dependent on geography, demography, and disease prevalence.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-25T16:25:13.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539638/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539638/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Primary Health Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an estimate of the potential savings that each clinical commissioning group could make through greater promotion of self-care for patients; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539639","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. Such information as is available is attached.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England publishes information on the number of attendances at all types of accident and emergency department. A type 3 accident and emergency department is one that treats minor injuries and illnesses (sprains for example) and can be routinely accessed without an appointment. In this context, minor ailments have been interpreted as a type 3 accident and emergency attendance.</p><p> </p><p>Data are reported to NHS England by all organisations providing National Health Service funded emergency care services and averaging more than 200 attendees per month. It is not possible to aggregate these data to clinical commissioning group, and the 10 strategic health authorities were abolished in March 2013. Published data for type 3 attendances are only available from 2011-12 onwards. These data are presented by 13 commissioning sub-regions, which are not legal entities but are sub-divisions of NHS England.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","43140","2016-07-21T15:16:06.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539639/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539639/answer","PQ43137 - DATA.xlsx","PQ43137 PQ43137 data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539639/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many accident and emergency visits there were for minor ailments in each clinical commissioning group in each year since 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539640","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally. However, information is available on the number of community pharmacies which are commissioned to provide a minor ailments service as an enhanced service under National Health Service pharmaceutical services at:</p><p> </p><p>www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB19026</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T17:00:13.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539640/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539640/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many visits there were to community pharmacies for minor ailments in (a) England and (b) each former strategic health authority area in each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539641","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>The then Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State (Jane Ellison) wrote to Vaughan Gething on 13 July 2016 to inform him of the publication of the Government Response to the Consultation on Reform of Financial and Other Support for those infected and affected by NHS supplied blood, and offered to arrange a call to discuss this further.</p><p> </p><p>Officials from the Department and the Welsh Government have been working together over the past few months on the issue of scheme reform, including a workshop in London in March to consider the themes emerging from the England consultation, and regular phone conferences.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-21T14:39:09.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539641/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539641/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had with the Welsh Government about financial support for victims of contaminated blood.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","43228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539642","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>The proportion of the National Health Service budget spent by NHS commissioners on the purchase of healthcare from private providers was 7.6% in 2015/16, as confirmed in the 2015-16 Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts. NHS commissioners purchase both healthcare and social care services from a range of private providers – a comprehensive list is not held centrally, but details of Government contracts held centrally can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-26T15:51:21.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539642/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539642/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of the NHS budget is spent on private providers which deliver NHS services; and if he will list those providers.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","43131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539643","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Under the Family Reunion Rules, children cannot sponsor family members. Any grant of leave in such cases would be on an exceptional basis outside the Immigration Rules. To obtain the information would involve examining individual case records and would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:10:41.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539643/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539643/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many children with refugee status in the UK have been granted permission to sponsor family members to join them under the refugee family reunion rules in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539644","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Stephen Shaw carried out a comprehensive consultation in preparing his report of his review of the welfare of vulnerable people in immigration detention, and the draft adults at risk policy forms part of the Government’s response to Mr Shaw’s review. The Government saw no reason to duplicate this in developing the adults at risk policy. However, when the draft policy was published on 26 May, the Government wrote to a wide range of relevant non-Governmental organisations and offered them the opportunity to discuss it. Subsequently, Home Office officials have held meetings with a number of interested organisations, and the views of these organisations have been taken into account as the policy has been developed further.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:11:30.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539644/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539644/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Detainees: Vulnerable Adults","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what consultation her Department has held on the draft Adults at Risk policy for vulnerable people detained under immigration powers.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539645","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Consideration is being given to arrangements for measuring the impact of the adults at risk policy and other initiatives aimed at improving the safeguarding of vulnerable people in immigration detention. The expectation is that these initiatives will result in a reduction in the number of the most vulnerable who are detained. The Government intends to ask Stephen Shaw to carry out a short review next year in order to assess progress against the key actions from his previous report.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:11:51.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539645/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539645/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Detainees: Vulnerable Adults","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how the effect of the Adults at Risk policy for vulnerable people detained under immigration powers will be measured.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539646","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Home Office has issued guidance to Immigration Enforcement caseworkers, enforcement officers and Border Force officers on the application of section 60 of the Immigration Act 2016. This was published on GOV.UK on 12 July, and includes monitoring tools to track the detention of pregnant women.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:09:22.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539646/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539646/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what mechanisms are in place to monitor the application of Section 60 of the Immigration Act 2016, on limitation on detention of pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539647","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-26","<p>I refer the hon. member to the answer given to PQ 42962 on 21 July 2016.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-07-26T16:08:55.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539647/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539647/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of legislation relating to online abuse on social media.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","43124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539648","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Customer service is a key priority for UK Visas and Immigration, and the efficiency and effectiveness of the visa application process is kept under regular review, including by the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration. Customers now apply and pay online in addition to being able to make appointments to submit their documents and biometrics at visa application centres in over 200 locations around the world.</p><p>The published service standard for resolving refugee family reunion applications is within 12 weeks, or 60 working days. Where an application is complex and likely to take longer than the advertised processing times, UKVI will contact the applicant to inform them of this.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:13:12.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539648/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539648/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to speed up the application process for refugee family reunion.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","43151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539649","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Under the Family Reunion Rules, children cannot sponsor family members. Any grant of leave in such cases would be on an exceptional basis outside the Immigration Rules. To obtain the information would involve examining individual case records and would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:10:25.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539649/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539649/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many children with refugee status in the UK have been granted permission to sponsor family members to join them under the refugee family reunion rules in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","43152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539650","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Government does not believe that it is appropriate for there to be a formal time limit on immigration detention.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:10:05.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539650/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539650/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to introduce a maximum limit on the length of time a person can be detained under immigration law.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","43149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539651","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Immigration Enforcement planning for 2016-17 and beyond will be reviewed by the new Secretary of State and published in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:12:35.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539651/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539651/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Immigration Enforcement Directorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Written Statement of 14 January 2016, HCWS470, when she plans to publish the Immigration Enforcement's Business Plan for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","43141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539652","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The current family reunion policy meets our international obligations and strikes the right balance. There are no plans to extend the criteria. Allowing children to sponsor parents would create perverse incentives for them to be encouraged, or even forced, to leave their family and risk hazardous journeys to the UK to sponsor relatives. This plays into the hands of criminal gangs who exploit vulnerable people and goes against our safe guarding responsibilities.</p><p>Where a family reunion application fails under the Immigration Rules we consider whether there are exceptional circumstances or compassionate reasons to justify granting a visa outside the Rules.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T14:54:58.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539652/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539652/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she intends to allow children with refugee status to sponsor their parents for the purposes of refugee family renunion.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","43150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539653","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>Refugees and people in Great Britain with humanitarian protection status who are disabled and in need of financial support are entitled to claim Jobseeker’s Allowance, Employment Support Allowance or Universal Credit, and Personal Independence Payment, providing they meet all the necessary conditions of entitlement set out in regulations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-21T12:27:17.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539653/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539653/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Refugees: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to make financial support available to refugees and people in Britain with humanitarian protection status who are disabled.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539654","Home Office","false","2016-07-25","<p>Updated country information and guidance on Eritrea will be published on the www.gov.uk website shortly.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-25T11:01:22.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539654/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539654/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539654/answer/previousversion/7903","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Asylum: Eritrea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish updated country guidance for asylum applications made by Eritrean nationals.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","43226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539655","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Government does not believe that it is appropriate for there to be a formal time limit on immigration detention.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-21T15:27:34.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539655/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539655/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will introduce a maximum limit on the length of time an individual can be detained under immigration powers.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","43225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539656","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information centrally. The purchase and deployment of speed enforcement devices is a local operational matter for individual police forces. There has been no assessment made on the merits of recruiting and training civilian volunteers in the use of these devices. Decisions on how the public can assist the police in speed enforcement activity are matters for individual Chief Officers.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-07-26T15:07:21.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539656/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539656/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Road Traffic Offences: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many hand-held radar speed detectors are in use by police constabularies in England; and whether her Department has made an assessment of the merits of recruiting and training civilian volunteers to use such detectors.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","43094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539657","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-21","<p>Legislation that can be used to prosecute online abuse and related offences includes the Protection from Harassment Act 1997; the Malicious Communications Act 1988; and the Communications Act 2003. The Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015 made changes to the relevant offences in these last two Acts which aim to ensure that people who commit them are prosecuted and properly punished.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that current legislation is sufficient and does not intend to consolidate existing legislation relating to online abuse and malicious communication.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-21T14:36:22.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539657/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539657/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","Internet: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will bring forward plans to consolidate existing legislation on online abuse and malicious communication.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539658","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>Whilst all asylum claims including those accepted under Dublin III are registered on the Home Office Case Information Database (CID), this data is not currently held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-21T15:15:56.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539658/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539658/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539658/answer/previousversion/7899","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many requests have been made by (a) France, (b) Greece and (c) Italy for the UK to take charge of an asylum application under the family reunification articles of the Dublin III Regulation in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","42992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539659","Home Office","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Home Office does not currently plan to change the data that is published on this category of applications. The question covers a number of different casework operations and the information is not recorded in a way which can be reported directly.</p><p>The Home Office keeps under review the statistics that are published in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics, balancing user needs against burdens on data suppliers.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-25T11:01:10.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539659/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539659/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539659/answer/previousversion/7901","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to publish the number of applications for refugee family reunion which were granted outside the rules in its quarterly migration statistics.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","42993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539660","Home Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>Customer service is a key priority for UK Visas and Immigration, and the efficiency and effectiveness of the visa application process is kept under regular review, including by the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration. The published service standard for resolving refugee family reunion applications is within 12 weeks, or 60 working days.</p><p>Where an application is complex and likely to take longer than the advertised processing times, UKVI will contact the applicant to inform them of this.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-21T14:57:52.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539660/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539660/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the time taken to process applications related to refugee family reunion.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","43003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539661","Home Office","false","2016-07-22","<p>The Criminal Justice Act 2015 strengthened two existing communications offences: section 1 of the Malicious Communications Act 1988, and section 127 of the Communications Act 2003 which can now be used to prosecute misuse of social media. The police now have longer to investigate either offence, and the maximum penalty for the former has been increased to two years imprisonment.</p><p>We have introduced a new law to make ‘revenge porn’ a specific criminal offence. Those convicted will face a maximum sentence of 2 years in prison. We have already seen convictions under this legislation and will continue to monitor its effectiveness.</p><p>To improve police capability, the Home Office has allocated £4.6m of the Police Transformation Fund to begin the critical work of setting up a comprehensive programme of digital transformation across policing. This money will help provide a step-change in digital capability, funding police led programmes that will work to equip forces with the tools to effectively police a digital age and protect victims of digital crime.</p><p>We are also working with the College of Policing to drive improvements in police capability to investigate and prosecute online Violence against Women and Girls offences. For example, we have introduced an ‘online flag’ allowing police forces to record instances of crimes such as stalking and harassment taking place online.</p><p>We are driving work through the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS) to keep children and young people safe online. UKCCIS brings together industry, law enforcement, academia, charities and parenting groups to help to keep children and young people safe online.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-07-22T21:34:00.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539661/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539661/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539661/answer/previousversion/7906","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Social Media: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle online abuse on social media.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","43024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539662","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>There are no immediate plans for changes to the format or colour of the UK passport. Parliament will be informed of any changes to the passport following UK withdrawal from the European Union.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:10:59.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539662/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539662/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take steps to introduce a new passport with a navy blue cover for the UK following the exit of the UK from the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","43057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539664","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Stephen Shaw carried out a comprehensive consultation in preparing his report of his review of the welfare of vulnerable people in immigration detention, and the draft adults at risk policy forms part of the Government’s response to Mr Shaw’s review. The Government saw no reason to duplicate this in developing the adults at risk policy. However, when the draft policy was published on 26 May, the Government wrote to a wide range of relevant non-Governmental organisations and offered them the opportunity to discuss it. Subsequently, Home Office officials have held meetings with a number of interested organisations, and the views of these organisations have been taken into account as the policy has been developed further.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:09:47.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539664/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539664/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Detainees: Vulnerable Adults","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what consultation her Department has undertaken on the draft Adults at Risk policy for vulnerable people detained under immigration powers.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","43061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539665","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The follow up to Stephen Shaw’s review into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons will take place in late 2017, with timings to be agreed with Mr Shaw.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-07-26T15:12:48.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539665/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539665/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Welfare in Detention of Vulnerable Persons Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for Stephen Shaw to complete his follow-up review of the use of immigration detention.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","43062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539666","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-21","<p>I am currently considering the outcomes of my Department’s Civil Society Partnership Review, and will aim to publish it shortly.</p><p>In July 2015, the then Secretary of State for International Development announced a 9 month extension of all PPA financing, providing 18 months-notice that all current PPA financing would come to an end in December 2016.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","43015","2016-07-21T14:59:54.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539666/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539666/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to replace programme partnership arrangements.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","43016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539667","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-21","<p>I am currently considering the outcomes of my Department’s Civil Society Partnership Review, and will aim to publish it shortly.</p><p>In July 2015, the then Secretary of State for International Development announced a 9 month extension of all PPA financing, providing 18 months-notice that all current PPA financing would come to an end in December 2016.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","43016","2016-07-21T14:59:54.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539667/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539667/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will consider extending current programme partnership arrangements until a replacement mechanism is introduced.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","43015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539668","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-22","<p>The table attached shows all PIDG supported projects. The table indicates whether the support for projects was initiated before or after 01 January 2010. As support for many projects initiated before 2010 will have continued into the timeframe set out in the question, we have also listed all projects where support was started before 01 January 2010. There is no other straightforward way to filter the data. Further information is also available online (<a href="http://data.pidg.org/" target="_blank">http://data.pidg.org/</a>) .</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-22T13:09:00.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539668/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539668/answer","PQ 43092.docx","PQ 43092","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539668/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Developing Countries: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which infrastructure projects were funded through or supported by the Private Infrastructure Development Group (PIDG) between 1 January 2010 and 30 June 2016; how much funding for each such project was (a) provided through PIDG and (b) leveraged from other sources; and whether each such project is operational.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","43092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539669","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-22","<p>The table attached shows all projects supported by GuarantCo. The table indicates whether the support for projects was initiated before or after 01 January 2010. As support for many projects initiated before 2010 will have continued into the timeframe set out in the question, we have also listed all projects where support was started before 01 January 2010. There is no other straightforward way to filter the data. Further information is also available online (<a href="http://data.pidg.org/" target="_blank">http://data.pidg.org/</a>) .</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-22T13:10:25.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539669/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539669/answer","PQ 43093.docx","PQ 43093","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539669/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Developing Countries: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which infrastructure projects were supported by borrowing guaranteed through GuarantCo between 1 January 2010 and 30 June 2016; how much was guaranteed for each such project; how much funding was leveraged from other sources for each such project; and whether each such project is operational.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","43093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539670","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-25","<p>The creation of the contingent liability in respect of the callable capital for GuarantCo does not have immediate budgetary implications and is not treated as Official Development Assistance (ODA). If the capital is called it will be treated as ODA. This is in line with the internationally agreed rules on ODA.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-25T11:28:14.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539670/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539670/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","GuarantCo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the proposed creation of a contingent liability of £40 million in respect of callable capital of GuarantCo is treated as Official Development Assistance (a) when the contingent liability is created and (b) in the event that capital is called from the public purse under the contingent liability.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","43091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539671","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-21","<p>In the last five calendar years, DFID spending in Africa on agriculture, fishing and forestry is set out below. Funds are spent through a range of delivery channels including private sector projects, challenge funds, funding through multilateral agencies and funding through African Governments.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p>£ thousands</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Agriculture, forestry and fishing</p></td><td><p>£33,327</p></td><td><p>£48,426</p></td><td><p>£45,354</p></td><td><p>£44,748</p></td><td><p>£61,350</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The private sector is vital for boosting food production in Africa. UK companies can participate in our projects to improve agricultural markets in a number of ways. The African Agriculture Development Fund (AgDevCo), which is a not for profit UK based company, invests debt and equity in African agribusinesses to create jobs, boost food security and increase prosperity. DFID is a principal funder of AgDevCo. UK companies are also implementers of our agriculture projects after winning competitive tenders. We share information with companies active in African agricultural markets either as buyers or investors. UK companies can be part of proposals to DFID funded challenge funds, such as the Africa Enterprise Challenge Fund, but only through their links to partner companies based in Africa rather than as direct beneficiaries.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-07-21T11:45:57.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539671/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539671/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Africa: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department has provided for food production projects in Africa in each of the last five years; and what involvement UK companies have had in such projects.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","43105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539672","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-20","<p>The United Nations’ 2016 Yemen Humanitarian Response Plan (YHRP), published in January 2016, reports that 21.2 million people in Yemen require some kind of humanitarian assistance to meet their basic needs or protect their fundamental rights, particularly for food, water and sanitation, healthcare, and support to internally displaced people. The YHRP is currently 26% funded with donations of £351 million. The UK has so far committed to spending £72 million in Yemen over 2016-17. We continue to call on other donors to provide funding for the crisis.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-20T13:32:59.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539672/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539672/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the need for humanitarian aid and assistance in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539673","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-25","<p>Transition planning and development of best practice is led by the relevant country office, with support from officials in the UK and across regions. Each transition process has been different depending on circumstance. ICAI is currently undertaking a review of DFID’s approach to transition and their report is due to be published towards the end of 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-07-25T11:29:01.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539673/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539673/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department employs staff with responsibility for developing best practice on withdrawing bilateral programmes from countries that transition to middle-income status.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","43167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539674","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-20","<p>The UK is the largest donor to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance. Between 2011 and 2015, the UK contributed £1.32 billion to Gavi. No additional administrative support was provided during this time.</p><p>The UK investment over the five year period between 2011 and 2015 immunised over 60 million children against vaccine preventable diseases which is estimated to have saved over 1 million lives.</p><p>Between 2016 and 2020, the UK is investing £1.44 billion in Gavi. This investment will deliver the Government’s manifesto commitment to immunise 76 million children against vaccine preventable diseases and save 1.4 million lives.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","43145 ; 43146","2016-07-20T14:59:02.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539674/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539674/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the financial contributions made by her Department to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539675","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-20","<p>The UK is the largest donor to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance. Between 2011 and 2015, the UK contributed £1.32 billion to Gavi. No additional administrative support was provided during this time.</p><p>The UK investment over the five year period between 2011 and 2015 immunised over 60 million children against vaccine preventable diseases which is estimated to have saved over 1 million lives.</p><p>Between 2016 and 2020, the UK is investing £1.44 billion in Gavi. This investment will deliver the Government’s manifesto commitment to immunise 76 million children against vaccine preventable diseases and save 1.4 million lives.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","43145 ; 43147","2016-07-20T14:59:02.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539675/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539675/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the financial contributions to be made by her Department to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539676","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-20","<p>The UK is the largest donor to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance. Between 2011 and 2015, the UK contributed £1.32 billion to Gavi. No additional administrative support was provided during this time.</p><p>The UK investment over the five year period between 2011 and 2015 immunised over 60 million children against vaccine preventable diseases which is estimated to have saved over 1 million lives.</p><p>Between 2016 and 2020, the UK is investing £1.44 billion in Gavi. This investment will deliver the Government’s manifesto commitment to immunise 76 million children against vaccine preventable diseases and save 1.4 million lives.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","43146 ; 43147","2016-07-20T14:59:01.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539676/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539676/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether administrative support has been provided by her Department to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539677","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-21","<p>Ethiopia is in the midst of its worst drought for 30 years, with 18.2 million people, approximately 20% of the population, in need of humanitarian assistance at the peak of the crisis. There has been a strong effort by the Government of Ethiopia and humanitarian partners to help save lives and safeguard livelihoods through provision of food, water and other essential supplies.</p><p>The UK Government has responded quickly and decisively since the onset of the drought in July 2015. So far, the UK Government has committed £145 million overall, making us the second largest donor to the response. This has included a commitment of £40 million to provide food aid to 3.8 million people in 2016 alone.</p><p>As Ethiopia moves into the traditional hungry period of July-September, the Government of Ethiopia and United Nations will revise their funding appeal, which is currently over a billion pounds and 70 % funded. The UK Government will continue to provide support and leadership to the humanitarian response in the coming months.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-07-21T11:43:52.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539677/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539677/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Ethiopia: Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effects of the food crisis in Ethiopia on people in that country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","43190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539678","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-21","<p>DFID has not provided direct financial support to local faith and church networks responding to the drought in Ethiopia. However, DFID has contributed £70.1 million over three years (2014-16) to the Ethiopia Humanitarian Response Fund (HRF), a pooled donor fund responding to the most urgent drought needs. DFID is the largest donor to the HRF (74% of current funding), which is administered by the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA).</p><p>In 2016 alone, the HRF has granted £40 million to 48 projects run by organizations, including World Vision and Catholic Relief Services, to bring food, water and emergency healthcare to over half a million of the most drought affected men, women and children in Ethiopia.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-07-21T11:56:59.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539678/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539678/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","Ethiopia: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support local faith and church networks in Ethiopia in their efforts to assist people affected by the current drought.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","43148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539679","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-21","<p>We will set out our proposals for a Bill of Rights in due course. We will consult fully on our proposals.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-21T14:27:10.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539679/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539679/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","Bill of Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she expects to bring forward proposals for a British Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","43209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539680","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Government is confident that the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (Cafcass) continues to provide high quality social work advice to support decisions by the courts in cases involving children. This reflects the outcome of the inspection in 2014 by the Office for Standards in Education (Ofsted) which judged that as a minimum all children, young people and families receive a service where the quality and effectiveness of Cafcass practice is ‘good’.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the department regularly assesses Cafcass’ efficiency and effectiveness and holds Cafcass to account for its performance, governance and stewardship of public funds.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","43060","2016-07-26T16:11:22.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539680/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539680/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","CAFCASS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment her Department has made of the performance of Cafcass.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","43059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539681","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Government is confident that the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (Cafcass) continues to provide high quality social work advice to support decisions by the courts in cases involving children. This reflects the outcome of the inspection in 2014 by the Office for Standards in Education (Ofsted) which judged that as a minimum all children, young people and families receive a service where the quality and effectiveness of Cafcass practice is ‘good’.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the department regularly assesses Cafcass’ efficiency and effectiveness and holds Cafcass to account for its performance, governance and stewardship of public funds.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","43059","2016-07-26T16:11:22.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539681/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539681/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","CAFCASS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department plans to carry out a review of the organisational efficiency and effectiveness of Cafcass.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","43060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539682","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not receive any funding from EU sources.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","42989","2016-07-25T14:18:18.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539682/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539682/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539682/answer/previousversion/7993","Biography information for James Brokenshire","21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-07-18","EU Grants and Loans: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what plans his Department has to mitigate any loss of funding resulting from the decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","42990"
