"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539693","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>Reforming the infected blood ex-gratia support schemes remain a priority for this Government and, at his last Prime Minister’s Questions on 13 July 2016, the then Prime Minister announced the publication of the Government’s plans for reforming the current payment support schemes for individuals affected by HIV and/or hepatitis C through National Health Service-supplied blood, including its response to the public consultation which ran earlier this year.</p><p> </p><p>The then Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Public Health (Jane Ellison) also issued a Written Ministerial Statement (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-07-14/HCWS88/" target="_blank">HCWS88</a>) on 14 July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The response document went live on the Gov.UK website on 13 July 2016 and can be found at:</p><p><br> <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/infected-blood-reform-of-financial-and-other-support" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/infected-blood-reform-of-financial-and-other-support</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-25T16:10:31.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539693/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539693/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the oral contribution of the previous Prime Minister on 13 July 2016, Official Report, column 291, on contaminated blood and compensation, when he expects the details of that scheme to be published.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","43206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539694","Prime Minister","false","2016-07-21","<p>I set out my priorities for government in my first statement as Prime Minister in Downing Street on 13 July 2016.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-07-21T16:56:27.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539694/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539694/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-07-18","Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she plans to fulfil all the legislative commitments made in the Queen's Speech on 18 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539695","Prime Minister","false","2016-07-21","<p>Information relating to the number of staff employed at Downing Street and their salaries is published as part of the Cabinet Office Staff and Salary Data, and is available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","43197 ; 43243 ; 43245","2016-07-21T16:56:19.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539695/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539695/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-07-18","Prime Minister: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has plans to change the number of staff employed by 10 Downing Street.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539696","Prime Minister","false","2016-07-21","<p>A list will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-07-21T16:57:21.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539696/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539696/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-07-18","Prime Minister: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what appointments she has made as her new special advisers since taking up her post.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539697","Prime Minister","false","2016-07-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the press release issued by my office on 14 July 2016. This is available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-07-21T16:57:04.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539697/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539697/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-07-18","Prime Ministers Policy Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, who the director of the Number 10 Policy Unit is.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539698","Scotland Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>While the United Kingdom remains a member of the European Union, we expect to retain the full benefits of membership, including the receipt of EU structural funds. Preparations for a negotiation to leave the EU should involve all the devolved administrations to make sure the interests of all parts of the UK are taken into account.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-07-20T11:20:27.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539698/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539698/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-07-18","EU Grants and Loans: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether projects in Scotland presently receiving EU structural funds will receive equivalent funding from the Government after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539699","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) has conducted the following numbers of manual traffic counts within the area covered by Bury St Edmunds constituency in each year since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>2010 17 counts</p><p>2011 16 counts</p><p>2012 16 counts</p><p>2013 16 counts</p><p>2014 16 counts</p><p>2015 13 counts</p><p> </p><p>These counts are carried out for the purpose of producing DfT’s statistics on traffic. They are conducted by observing traffic unobtrusively at designated locations and consequently have no impact on the traffic flows.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T09:59:36.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539699/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539699/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Road Traffic: Bury St Edmunds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many traffic surveys and counts his Department has conducted in Bury St Edmunds constituency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539700","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department published “The national safety camera programme: Four-year evaluation report” in December 2005. The Road Safety Observatory, of which the Department is a member, published “Effectiveness Of Speed Cameras In Preventing Road Traffic Collisions And Related Casualties: Systematic Review” in March 2013. No research has been carried out of the effect of conspicuously marking cameras.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T14:30:59.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539700/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539700/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent research his Department has conducted on (a) the merits of static speed cameras and (b) the effect of conspicuously marking such cameras on their effectiveness.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","43095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539701","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Access for All programme has delivered accessible step-free routes at over 150 stations since 2006, with smaller scale access improvements at more than 1,500 stations. To build on this success, we made a further £160m available to extend the programme, providing step-free routes at a further 68 stations. This is in addition to access improvements delivered as part of other major projects, such as Crossrail which will deliver step-free routes at another 40 stations. No decision has been made on the overall rail funding package, including funding for accessibility improvements, for Control Period 6 (2019-2024).</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-07-21T15:26:52.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539701/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539701/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Railway Stations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he has made on providing a further round of accessibility funding for (a) lifts and (b) other accessibility devices at mainline railway stations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","43142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539702","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>(a) Highways England do not collect shortest road journey information, however information available via online route planning tools shows that a journey from London Charing Cross to Birmingham Town Hall, via the A40, M40, M42 and A34 requires a journey of 118 miles (b) 113 miles between London Euston and Birmingham New Street. The distance between the principal Birmingham station and nearest London terminal and (c) approximately 109 miles to the nearest mile.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T14:22:50.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539702/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539702/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the official distances between London and Birmingham are for the (a) shortest journey by road, (b) shortest existing journey by rail and (c) projected High Speed 2 line.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","42979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539703","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>Actual performance against the performance benchmarks are calculated each four-weekly railway period, not on a weekly basis. Therefore, the Department does not have the information requested for the period 11 to 18 July 2016.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-07-21T15:23:54.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539703/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539703/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the performance of Southern Railway Limited for the period 11 to 18 July 2016 met the specified benchmarks in the Remedial Plan.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","42957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539704","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>My Department has not received any such representations.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-07-21T15:18:57.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539704/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539704/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Thameslink Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2016 to Question 40332, on Thameslink railway line: rolling stock, whether his Department has received any representations from trade unions on the potential safety implications of operating Class 700 trains under Driver Only Operation or Driver Controlled Operation.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539705","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department has appointed a team of solicitors, Parliamentary Agents and barristers to support the HS2 project. Tim Mould QC is primarily employed to support the HS2 hybrid Bill process which gives those affected by HS2 an opportunity to present their concerns in Parliament. Since 2013 the Department for Transport has paid £679,567.10 to Tim Mould QC to support the HS2 project on Bill related matters. This figure is correct to 19 July 2016 and is exclusive of VAT.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, since approximately 2010, the Department has also instructed a number of barristers, including Tim Mould QC, on other HS2 related matters, primarily litigation. These barristers will have been remunerated at government hourly rates agreed with the Attorney General, but it would involve disproportionate cost for the Department to provide precise figures.</p><p> </p><p>The use of barristers to support the HS2 project is demand led and so it is not possible to forecast the fees that may be paid to Tim Mould QC in the future.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T14:26:55.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539705/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539705/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which fees (a) have been paid and (b) are due to be paid to Tim Mould QC for work relating to High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","43023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539706","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-26","<p>For the period of 2011/12 – 2015/16 HS2 Ltd has incurred the following costs associated with press liaison, publicity and marketing of HS2:</p><p> </p><p>(a) staff - £0.9m. This is the total payroll cost for HS2 Ltd staff (i.e. permanent staff). This excludes contingent labour and secondees;</p><p> </p><p>(b) recruitment - HS2 Ltd incurs, manages and controls its recruitment costs centrally and, as such, it is not possible to identify the costs incurred in specific business functions; and</p><p> </p><p>(c) other costs of press liaison, publicity and marketing of High Speed 2 - £1.1m</p><p> </p><p>Expenditure prior to 2011/12 was not broken down by expenditure type in this way.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-26T09:32:42.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539706/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539706/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) staff, (b) recruitment and (c) other costs of press liaison, publicity and marketing of High Speed 2 have been to date.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","43088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539707","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>Our global connections are crucial for British business and benefit the whole country. The economic benefits to the UK as a whole, not just London and the South East, will be taken into consideration when making a decision on a preferred scheme for airport expansion, alongside a range of other relevant evidence.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T13:59:45.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539707/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539707/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic benefit to Bradford of any expansion of Heathrow.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","43029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539708","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>Determining which local road improvement schemes will offer the greatest benefit to the local economy is a matter for the West Yorkshire Combined Authority and the five constituent Local Authorities.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Roads Investment Strategy, Highways England’s Delivery Plan for the Strategic Road Network includes a number of improvements which will improve connectivity between Huddersfield and Bradford. As well as providing additional capacity, these improvements will also present the opportunity to release additional land along the corridor for development, which will support economic growth in West Yorkshire.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-21T14:35:25.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539708/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539708/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Roads: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic effect on the West Yorkshire area of improvement of the road network between Huddersfield and Bradford.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539709","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>This Government is committing investment to improve the M62 by upgrading to Smart Motorway between Junction 20 and 25. Additional funding was also announced at the Budget (2016) to bring forward the start of works to mid 2019-2020.</p><p>Proposals to improve the M62 from post-2020 will be considered as we prepare the second Road Investment Strategy – announced at Budget 2016. As part of the evidence-gathering process, Highways England is revisiting its Route Strategies to examine issues right across England’s motorways and major trunk roads. MPs and stakeholders are encouraged to engage with Highways England throughout this process.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-07-21T12:41:31.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539709/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539709/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","M62: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic effect on the West Yorkshire area of an additional junction on the M62 between junctions 24 and 25.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539710","Wales Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>As My Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister made clear during her meeting with the First Minister on Monday, the Welsh Government and other devolved administrations will be fully involved in preparations for a negotiation to leave the EU to ensure that the interests of all parts of the United Kingdom are protected and advanced.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-07-21T10:25:52.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539710/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539710/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-07-18","Brexit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what role the Welsh Government will have in negotiating the terms of the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","43231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539711","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>We are committed to halving the disability employment gap between disabled and non disabled people and have introduced a number of measures to further the support available to young people with disabilities, and long-term health conditions.</p><p> </p><p>A Taskforce, led by Paul Maynard MP, has been looking at issues around apprenticeships for people with learning difficulties or disabilities. On 11 July the Department for Work and Pensions, the Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills and the Department for Education published their response to the task force accepting all their recommendations including adjustments in English and maths requirements for those with learning disabilities. The publication can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeships-improving-access-for-people-with-learning-disabilities" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/apprenticeships-improving-access-for-people-with-learning-disabilities</a>.</p><p> </p><p>This Department has also developed a portal for young people with disabilities and health conditions to signpost them to available support. This can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/help-and-support-for-young-disabled-people-to-find-and-stay-in-work/help-and-support-for-young-disabled-people-to-find-and-stay-in-work" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/help-and-support-for-young-disabled-people-to-find-and-stay-in-work/help-and-support-for-young-disabled-people-to-find-and-stay-in-work</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Young disabled people and those with health conditions may also be supported by DWP’s specialist disability employment programmes such as Work Programme, Work Choice, Specialist Employment Support and Access to Work, subject to meeting eligibility criteria. Access to Work can provide support for young people participating on Traineeships or Supported Internships as well as those in work including apprenticeships. In 2015/16 Access to Work supported 2,830 young people aged 16-24, An increase of 12.7% over the previous year and the highest number since 2007/08 (beginning of our current records).</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we have expanded Access to Work’s Mental Health Support Service to conduct a two-year trial of targeted support for apprentices with mental health conditions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-21T13:16:22.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539711/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539711/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to support young people with (a) disabilities and (b) long-term health conditions to find permanent employment.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539712","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>Refugees and people in Great Britain with humanitarian protection status who are disabled and in need of financial support are entitled to claim Jobseeker’s Allowance, Employment Support Allowance or Universal Credit, and Personal Independence Payment, providing they meet all the necessary conditions of entitlement set out in regulations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-21T15:40:52.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539712/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539712/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Social Security Benefits: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether people resident in Britain with (a) refugee or (b) humanitarian protection status can claim (i) personal independence payments and (ii) employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539713","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information requested is available in the official Universal Credit statistics: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-21T13:05:35.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539713/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539713/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Universal Credit: Bury St Edmunds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants there were in Bury St Edmunds constituency in (a) June 2015, (b) December 2015 and (c) the latest month for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539714","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-26","<p>The figures in the table below provide the number of (a) workers and (b) members of the public who have been reported to HSE under the Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences 2013 (RIDDOR), as being injured in accidents at funfairs and amusement parks from 2012. Data collected prior to 2012 is not directly comparable due to changes in reporting and recording criteria.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1 - Injuries to workers and members of the public in funfairs and amusement parks</strong><sup>1</sup><strong> as reported to all enforcing authorities 2012/13 – 2014/15p</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year<sup>3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Public</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Workers­­<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>479</p></td><td><p>64</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>387</p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15<sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p>489</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>1 Statistics are identified by Standard Industrial Classification 2007 (SIC 2007) class 9321 – Activities of amusement parks and theme parks</p><p>2 The term worker includes employees and self-employed persons combined</p><p>3 Due to changes in legislation, the criteria for reporting injuries to workers changed in April 2012 and again in October 2013. Therefore annual estimates of injuries to workers over this period are not directly comparable</p><p>4 HSE’s analysis of the data for injuries to members of the public at fairgrounds and theme parks in 2014/15 found that upwards of 75% of reported injuries did not meet the criteria for a RIDDOR reportable injury.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-26T13:53:47.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539714/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539714/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Fairgrounds: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many accidents have occurred at funfairs and amusement parks in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539715","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-22","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) has a dedicated National Fairground Inspection Team (NFIT) which enforces health and safety law at fairgrounds and theme parks in Great Britain. The NFIT work plan for 2106/17 targets proactive inspection of fairground rides with known problems and other areas of higher risk.</p><p> </p><p>NFIT inspectors also investigate accidents and complaints. They have a range of options available to hold poor performers to account, including enforcement notices and prosecution for the most serious breaches of the law. Any lessons learned from these investigations are communicated to the industry.</p><p> </p><p>HSE is also working with national industry bodies, which collectively make up the Amusement Devices Safety Council, to maintain and where necessary, improve health and safety standards and practices across the industry. HSE is currently working with one of those bodies, the British Association Leisure Parks Piers and Attractions, on an initiative aimed at improving risk management at theme parks.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-22T10:20:24.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539715/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539715/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Fairgrounds: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to prevent accidents at funfairs and amusement parks.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539716","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>Allowing claimants to upload evidence and supporting documentation safely and securely is a crucial element as we build and develop the full online Universal Credit Service; for example, claimants can already upload CVs and covering letters for their work coach to review, and this facility will be expanded to include other documents as the service rolls out.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-21T12:54:07.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539716/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539716/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Social Security Benefits: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress his Department has made on introducing a secure online portal through which new claimants of working-age benefits can submit supporting evidence and documents.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","42985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539717","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>There are no plans to conduct a public consultation as part of the 30 month review. The Review will draw on information from externally commissioned qualitative and quantitative surveys conducted with those who use the Child Maintenance Service, as well as analysis of national data on separated families, including those who have chosen not to make maintenance arrangements through the statutory systems. We have also engaged with a number of relevant external stakeholder organisations who have been invited to provide a written response to a series of questions on charging.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-07-21T12:42:45.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539717/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539717/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a public consultation will form part of the 30-month review of the introduction of child maintenance service changes.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","42974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539718","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-26","<p>Breakdowns of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims made by Disability Living Allowance (DLA) claimants in payment by type and rate of awards, and reassessment claims by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn), can be found at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>The Department does not have verified data on the number of PIP claimants who have had their payments reduced as a result of the move to PIP. We intend to provide more detailed breakdowns of DLA to PIP reassessment outcomes in due course. The Department is working to guidelines set by the UK Statistics Authority to ensure we are able to publish statistics that meet high quality standards at the earliest opportunity.</p><p>The Department does not hold data on whether a DLA recipient has leased a car under the Motability scheme.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-26T12:48:59.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539718/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539718/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have (a) had their payments reduced and (b) lost their motability cars after transferring from disability living allowance to personal independence payments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","43073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539719","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>The general rule is that a tribunal’s decision will take effect from the same date as that of the decision under appeal – as determined by the Secretary of State. However, as a tribunal considers all appealed decisions afresh, it may decide that a different date is more appropriate.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-21T13:11:33.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539719/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539719/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on backdating payments for personal independence payment applicants who receive an uprating as a result of a tribunal ruling; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","43074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539720","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) demonstrates a duty of care throughout all its customer services and which it expects its staff to follow through instructions and learning.</p><p>The Department has an established approach to identifying and providing an appropriate level of support to all its customers who are vulnerable, including those with mental health conditions. DWP identifies any “individual who is identified as having complex needs and/or requires additional support to enable them to access DWP benefits and use our services” as being vulnerable. This definition ensures that we have consistency and continuity in the type and level of service which is being offered and that it supports the customer appropriately whatever their needs.</p><p>DWP’s approach for dealing specifically with customers experiencing mental health conditions has been developed in consultation with its Work Psychologists to ensure that staff are able to develop a thorough understanding of the various different mental health conditions which exist, including hidden impairments and how they impact on an individual. This knowledge is reflected in both DWP instructions and in its learning and development.</p><p>Where DWP staff are satisfied that a customer faces clear and significant risks to their welfare or safety, then those staff are explicitly empowered by DWP to take any reasonable steps which are felt necessary, including liaising with relevant organisations, in order to address these risks without undue delay.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-21T16:19:27.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539720/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539720/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Jobcentre Plus: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the minimum requirements set by his Department are for Jobcentre Plus to ensure that it is not neglectful in its duty of care towards a claimant who has (a) been attending a psychiatric unit, (b) has a known history of mental illness or (c) has a social worker designated to them; and what guidance his Department provides to Jobcentre Plus on providing such duty of care.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","43098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539721","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-21","<p>The government launched the HM Treasury Women in Finance Charter to take forward Jayne-Anne Gadhia’s recommendations following her review into the representation of senior women in financial services.</p><p> </p><p>Firms that have signed the Charter are committed to implementing four key industry actions to improve gender diversity in financial services. On 11 July the government announced that 72 firms have signed the Charter. Together these firms employ over 530,000 people in the UK, with headquarters across the UK, USA, Europe and Asia.</p><p> </p><p>Harnessing the talents of women in financial services is one of the government’s key priorities and we are committed to encouraging as many financial services firms as possible to sign the Women in Finance Charter.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-07-21T15:12:55.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539721/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539721/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Women in Finance Charter","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will encourage companies to sign up to the Women in Finance Charter.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","43106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539722","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-25","<p>A list of Special Advisers in Government will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-25T12:58:52.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539722/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539722/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whom he has appointed as his special advisers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539723","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-02","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We are looking to provide a range of innovation finance products to meet the needs of businesses, which will include loans, grants, and other types of innovation finance. Some of our competitor economies (like France, Finland, and the Netherlands) use a variety of financial instruments to support innovative businesses. We have engaged with their innovation agencies to learn from these established approaches to support, drive and encourage innovation in the UK. We are conducting market research to engage with, and fully understand the needs of, innovative businesses of all sizes and across many UK industry sectors with a high level of innovation, including life sciences. As part of the first phase of implementation the Government will announce the details of a pilot and accompanying evaluation in late 2016. The pilot will test specific financial products ahead of progressing to full roll-out.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-08-02T13:48:42.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539723/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539723/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the suitability of proposed new innovation finance products for life sciences research and development and other high-risk innovation sectors.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","43083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539724","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>(a) The current allocation for staff in the UK National Contact Point is half a Grade 7, one full-time Senior executive officer and one full-time Higher executive officer.</p><p> </p><p>(b) None in other Departments.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:51:05.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539724/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539724/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many full-time equivalent officials in (a) his Department and (b) other government departments work in the National Contact Point for the OECD Guidelines; and what the grades are of those officials.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","43211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539725","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-21","<p>Responsibility for digital consumer rights sits with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. Protecting consumer rights is an important issue and will remain a priority for the department.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-07-21T16:08:55.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539725/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539725/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether responsibility for digital consumer rights sits within his Department.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","43222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539726","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-10","<p>The Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership Growth Service connects entrepreneurs and businesses to the right help for their needs. It works with public and private sector partners – for example, chambers of commerce, universities, the national Business Support Helpline and banks – to refer businesses to the appropriate expert advice and support, including Start Up loans and the Start and Grow programme. The Leeds City Region Enterprise Partnership Growth Service is one of 39 growth hubs across the country that receives funding from my Department.</p><p> </p><p>58,000 businesses were newly registered for VAT or PAYE in the Leeds City Region during 2010 to 2014.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-10T06:53:30.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539726/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539726/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","New Businesses: Leeds City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support his Department provides to people in the Leeds City Region who wish to start their own business.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539727","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for the Digital Single Market sits with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, and responsibility for the Digital Economy sits with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-07-21T16:06:51.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539727/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539727/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether responsibility for the Digital Single Market and the digital economy sits within his Department.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","43223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539728","Department for Education","false","2016-08-02","<p>There are no immediate changes following the EU Referendum, including in the circumstances of British citizens studying, or planning to study, in the EU. Future arrangements for studying abroad will need to be considered as part of wider discussions about the UK’s relationship with the EU. For further information, see the Government Statement at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-on-higher-education-and-research-following-the-eu-referendum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-on-higher-education-and-research-following-the-eu-referendum</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-08-02T13:52:13.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539728/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539728/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Foreign Students: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on the ability of UK students studying language courses to work, study and live in other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539729","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-10","<p>The employment rate is at a record high. Government is committed to ensuring that UK remains open for business, and continues to grow and thrive. Our recent UK Innovation survey report confirms business innovation is growing across the UK and Yorkshire and Humber leads the way as the most innovative region. Government has awarded £1.19 billion in Growth Deals to the Local Enterprise Partnerships in the region so far which is forecast to attract £1.62 billion of co-investment and create 39,000 jobs.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-10T07:07:23.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539729/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539729/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Employment: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to protect employment levels in the Yorkshire and Humber region from the potential (a) immediate and (b) short to long-term effects of the UK withdrawing from the EU.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","43113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539730","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-21","<p>I have been asked to reply on behalf of the Department for International Trade.</p><p>Under the machinery of government changes announced recently the UK NCP will now be located in the Department for International Trade.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:55:39.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539730/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539730/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether, following the recent machinery of government changes, the National Contact Point for the OECD Guidelines is still based in his Department.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","43210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539732","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-15","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Responsibility for developing and implementing an industrial strategy clearly sits within the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. We will be working closely across Government and with a range of organisations – including regional representatives, businesses, trade and research bodies, universities, and trade unions - to deliver this, to help ensure that the economy grows strongly in all parts of the country, and to support the UK’s global competitiveness.</p><p> </p><p>We will be engaging with all sectors, including the steel industry through the Steel Council, to understand issues common to multiple sectors, and where Government needs to focus its effort to support UK businesses.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","42968","2016-08-15T12:59:08.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539732/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539732/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's policy is on including the steel industry in its industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539733","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-15","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Responsibility for developing and implementing an industrial strategy clearly sits within the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. We will be working closely across Government and with a range of organisations – including regional representatives, businesses, trade and research bodies, universities, and trade unions - to deliver this, to help ensure that the economy grows strongly in all parts of the country, and to support the UK’s global competitiveness.</p><p> </p><p>We will be engaging with all sectors, including the steel industry through the Steel Council, to understand issues common to multiple sectors, and where Government needs to focus its effort to support UK businesses.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","42967","2016-08-15T12:59:08.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539733/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539733/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's responsibilities are on developing and implementing an industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539734","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-25","<p>When a business changes owner, TUPE regulations may apply. Outsourcing part of their business is a commercial decision taken by British Airways and it is not a matter for the Government to investigate such decisions.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-25T12:53:03.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539734/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539734/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","British Airways: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will investigate whether TUPE provisions have been applied to British Airways IT workers' jobs that have been outsourced in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","42998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539735","Department for Education","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Higher Education and Research Bill provides for powers to vary or revoke Degree Awarding Powers. We plan to set out the proposed changes to the exact Degree Awarding Powers requirements and processes in new DfE criteria and guidance. The department intends to consult on the detail before publishing this guidance. Subject to the passage of the bill, we intend to consult before summer 2017.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-08-02T13:47:50.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539735/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539735/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Higher Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2016 to Question 42021, if she will make it her policy to consult on the detail of the proposed changes to the Degree Awarding Powers before the Higher Education and Research Bill becomes law.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","42984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539736","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-21","<p>Following the Machinery of Government changes, budgets will be formally agreed and approved by Parliament through the relevant Supply Estimate process. The next Estimate will be published in early 2017. The Department is working through the budgetary implications of the recent MOG announcements in advance of this.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-07-21T15:59:33.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539736/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539736/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of his Department's total budget in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539737","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-21","<p>All the Civil Servants previously employed by the Department for Energy and Climate Change have moved to the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. All of its functions, along with the business, industrial strategy, science and innovation functions of the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills have come together to form the new Department.</p><p> </p><p>Details of staff numbers at the former Department for Energy and Climate Change were published in its Annual Report and Accounts 2015/16 on 13 July 2016</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-07-21T15:57:05.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539737/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539737/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Civil Servants employed by the Department for Energy and Climate Change he expects to move to employment in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539738","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-25","<p>As part of its responsibility for maintaining the UK companies register, Companies House undertake some basic checks on companies during the incorporation process. The Government has no current plans to require additional processes and checks before registration.</p><p> </p><p>Companies House maintains statistics on the nature of the complaints it receives about alleged address fraud.</p><p> </p><p>Companies House follows up on all complaints received about newly incorporated companies and works closely with law enforcement agencies where fraudulent activity is suspected. It is an offence under the Companies Act to submit false information to Companies House.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-08-25T12:49:42.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539738/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539738/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on the level of address fraud in the registration of companies; and if his Department will seek to review the process and legislation for the registration of companies in order to avoid such fraud in future.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","43058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539739","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>There are currently in excess of 50 civil servants in my Department primarily working on trade policy. They are assisted by officials in other Government Departments, notably the Department for Exiting the EU, the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, the Department for International Development and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, as well as by other officials within my Department for whom trade policy is not their primary responsibility.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:38:38.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539739/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539739/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many trade specialists are currently employed by his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539740","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Department for International Trade is currently being established. This requires machinery of government changes which are ongoing.</p><p> </p><p>Parliamentary budget delegations will be amended in due course.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:23:18.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539740/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539740/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Department for International Trade: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of his Department's total budget in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539741","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-25","<p>HMRC special analysis showing the value of shellfish exports from England and Scotland is set out in the table below. Data are provisional and subject to revision.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Exports of shellfish (£million)</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>April 2015 to March 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>191</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>185</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: HMRC special analysis of Regional Trade Statistics database</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-07-25T14:20:12.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539741/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539741/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Shellfish: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much shellfish was exported from (a) England and (b) Scotland in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","43001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539742","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-25","<p>HMRC special analysis showing the value of Scotch Whisky exports from England and Scotland is set out in the table below. Data are provisional and subject to revision.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Exports of Scotch Whisky (£million)</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>April 2015 to March 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>144</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>3,554</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: HMRC special analysis of Regional Trade Statistics database</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-07-25T14:27:54.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539742/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539742/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Whisky: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much Scotch whisky was exported from (a) England and (b) Scotland in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","43000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539743","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-22","<p>The Department for International Trade is currently being established. This requires machinery of government changes which are ongoing; it is too early to say the exact number of officials that will be employed in the new Department. We will inform the House in due course.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-07-22T13:23:58.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539743/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539743/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the number of officials that will be employed by his Department in each of the next three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539744","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-25","<p>Since 2010 the Government has succeeded in reducing the trade deficit by £4bn or 9.4% through a number of measures delivered by UKTI such as the Exporting is GREAT campaign. We will continue this work and boost our delivery of assistance to British business through new initiatives such as the Directory of Exporters, due to be formally launched in November, and other measures.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-07-25T14:22:13.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539744/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539744/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Balance of Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he plans to take to reduce the UK's trade deficit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539745","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>The UK Government is committed to ensuring developing countries can reduce poverty through trading opportunities. Trading arrangements that do not involve developing countries can still have an impact on them. Such impacts will be taken into account as the UK develops its international trade policy.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:36:25.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539745/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539745/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Developing Countries: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether UK trade negotiators will be instructed to consider the risks and opportunities for poverty reduction in the least developed countries during future negotiations of trade deals.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","43100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539746","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>The UK Government is committed to ensuring developing countries can reduce poverty through trading opportunities. As the UK prepares to leave the EU there will be no initial change in the way we trade with developing countries. The UK has a unique opportunity to shape a bright future for the UK and its trading relationship with developing countries.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-07-21T16:34:29.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539746/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539746/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Developing Countries: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK's future trade agreements take into account their potential effect on exports from the least developed countries to the UK.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","43101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539747","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Government is continuing to drive progress against its manifesto commitments of having 100,000 more UK companies exporting in 2020 than in 2010 and reaching £1 trillion exports in 2020. To support these efforts, the Prime Minister created the Department for International Trade, which will develop, coordinate and deliver trade and investment policy to promote UK business across the globe.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-07-21T16:49:20.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539747/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539747/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he plans to maintain the target set by the last Government to raise the level of British exports to £1 trillion by 2020.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539748","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-26","<p>A list of Special Advisers in Government will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2016-07-26T08:46:39.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539748/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539748/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Department for International Trade: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, who he has appointed as his new special advisers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539749","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>Cabinet Members are entitled to two special advisers. These appointments will be made in the coming days and weeks.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-07-27T09:20:36.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539749/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whom he has appointed as his new special advisers.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539750","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>We continue to receive views across the range of the Department’s responsibilities following the outcome of the EU Referendum. Defra will be working on our future policies in this area, liaising closely with other key departments on future support for agriculture, animal welfare, and the food and drink industry. The Government will work with industry and the public to develop these new arrangements.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43204 ; 43205","2016-07-27T09:26:41.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539750/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539750/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will, in his negotiations to leave the EU, retain production chain food traceability measures for live animals, animal-based products and plants.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539751","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>The Government will fully involve the devolved administrations, including Scotland, as we prepare for negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU. We are working towards securing the best possible deal for the whole UK. The Government will continue to consult a broad range of stakeholders, including governments and business, on the implications of the referendum result.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-07-27T09:23:49.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539751/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will, in his negotiations to leave the EU, ensure that the agreement puts no legal obstacle in the way of the Scottish Government's policy of minimum alcohol pricing.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539752","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>We continue to receive views across the range of the Department’s responsibilities following the outcome of the EU Referendum. Defra will be working on our future policies in this area, liaising closely with other key departments on future support for agriculture, animal welfare, and the food and drink industry. The Government will work with industry and the public to develop these new arrangements.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43202 ; 43205","2016-07-27T09:26:41.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539752/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will, in his negotiations to leave the EU, retain common European control of food standards, animal feed safety and food hygiene.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539753","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>We continue to receive views across the range of the Department’s responsibilities following the outcome of the EU Referendum. Defra will be working on our future policies in this area, liaising closely with other key departments on future support for agriculture, animal welfare, and the food and drink industry. The Government will work with industry and the public to develop these new arrangements.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43202 ; 43204","2016-07-27T09:26:41.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539753/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will, in his negotiations to leave the EU, retain free movement of animals as (a) pets and (b) farm animals.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539754","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff from various departments across Government. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are under consideration.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43032 ; 43282","2016-07-27T09:19:08.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539754/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539754/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the number of officials that will be employed by his Department in each of the next three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539755","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>We continue to receive views across the range of the Department’s responsibilities following the outcome of the EU Referendum. Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the EU and current EU funding arrangements will continue unchanged. Defra will be liaising closely with other key departments, the industry and the public on future support for agriculture and its beneficiaries.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-07-27T09:25:30.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539755/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539755/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Common Agricultural Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he plans to take during negotiations on leaving the EU to ensure that people in the UK who benefit from the Common Agricultural Policy are not disadvantaged by the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","43187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539756","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>The rights retained by EU nationals here and British citizens in other EU states once the UK has left the European Union will be agreed during the course of negotiations. The Government fully expects that the legal status of EU nationals in the UK will be properly protected when we leave the EU. We also expect the same for British nationals in other EU Member States.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43239","2016-07-27T09:27:59.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539756/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539756/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","EU Countries: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with other EU member states on the rights of UK nationals living in those countries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","43189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539757","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff from various departments across Government. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are under consideration.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43144 ; 43282","2016-07-27T09:19:08.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539757/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539757/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many officials his Department will have once it is fully staffed; and by what date he expects his Department to be fully staffed.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539758","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-27","<p>The Government will fully involve the devolved administrations, including Scotland, as we prepare for negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU. We are working towards securing the best possible deal for the whole UK, and to achieve this we will need to work closely with colleagues in the devolved administrations at official and ministerial level. I addressed this subject in greater detail in the debate held on 21 July: <a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-07-21/debates/16072153000001/EUExitDevolvedGovernments" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-07-21/debates/16072153000001/EUExitDevolvedGovernments</a></p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43284","2016-07-27T09:22:23.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539758/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539758/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what role the Scottish Government and other devolved administrations have in negotiating with the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","43033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539759","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-07-21","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union is taking the necessary steps to equip itself to oversee negotiations to leave the EU and establish the future relationship between the UK and EU. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are now being considered.</p>","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis",,"2016-07-21T10:06:13.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539759/answer","Biography information for Mr David Davis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539759/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-18","Department for Exiting the European Union: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the total budget for his Department in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539760","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-21","<p>I am pleased to report that over 1,000 young people in Suffolk have participated in NCS in the past two years. The NCS Trust does not collect data at a constituency level. Therefore, the figures below are for the local authority area of Suffolk.</p><p> </p><p>2014 – 328 participants</p><p>2015 – 710 participants</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-07-21T15:07:29.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539760/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539760/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-18","Voluntary Work: Bury St Edmunds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many young people in Bury St Edmunds constituency participated in the National Citizen Service in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539762","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>For claims from 2013-14 NHS trusts are responsible for repaying any overpaid tax or National Insurance contributions in respect of trainees on the Widening Access Scheme. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is working closely with the Trusts to ensure that the rules are correctly applied and NHS trainees receive refunds as quickly as possible. For earlier years HMRC is working through claims from trainees and repaying them directly.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-26T07:55:14.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539762/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539762/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","NHS: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessments has HM Revenue and Customs made of the effectiveness of repaying overpaid national insurance and income tax to NHS trainees under the widening access fund.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","43279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539763","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Government has a duty under section 165 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to carry out a review of the minimum energy performance requirements for new homes in the Building Regulations. Work on the review is under way.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-07-25T15:53:10.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539763/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539763/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Government plans to set new carbon standards for the new-build housing sector.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539764","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-21","<p>Through DCLG grant funding, the Local Government Association (LGA) provides broad support to the local government sector, including training and support for members and officers, and policy briefings. This includes one-to-one mentoring for elected leaders and cabinet members by other member peers, members attending LGA Leadership Academy programmes, and corporate peer challenges. Corporate peer challenges involve a team of senior members and officers from other areas spending time in a council to review and challenge an aspect of its activity.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-21T15:58:56.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539764/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539764/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Local Government Executive: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to improve the training offered to (a) the leaders of local authorities and (b) local authority cabinet members.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539765","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Government does not collect data relating to pub closures. However, it recognises the clear social and economic value of our pubs, including many of those in the Ribble Valley, not least the award-winning Swan with Two Necks at Pendleton, and is supporting them through a range of measures. These include helping communities to buy their locals through the new £3.62 million 'More than a Pub' programme; giving communities reasonable time to bid to buy their pub should it be put up for sale by listing it as an Asset of Community Value with their local authority; and freezing beer duty at Budget 2016, which followed an unprecedented cut in duty in each of the preceding three budgets, and the scrapping of the beer escalator at Budget 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-21T16:13:16.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539765/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539765/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Public Houses: Ribble Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many pubs have closed down in the Ribble Valley in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","43269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539766","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-21","<p>Local councillors play a vital role in providing leadership, a voice for local communities and in overseeing key public services. So it is important that political parties and the local government sector encourage high calibre candidates from a wide range of backgrounds and experiences to put themselves forward to become local councillor candidates. The Local Government Association runs a programme to increase the diverse pool of talent from which councillors are elected to serve in local government.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-21T16:11:24.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539766/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539766/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Councillors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to encourage high quality candidates with (a) public and (b) private sector experience to become councillors.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539767","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-22","<p>We do not hold take-up data at constituency level.</p><p> </p><p>Take-up in the areas covered by the BDUK projects is available at: <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=0" target="_blank">https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Hs00bNsyRV1WoOt-fow3rsNXzpcKg26AsOWvk1bvJRk/edit#gid=0</a></p><p> </p><p>Ofcom’s, “Connected Nations 2015” publication indicates that “one in three homes had ‘superfast’ broadband with a connection of 30 Mbit/s or more&quot; in May 2015.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-07-22T13:24:23.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539767/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539767/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-18","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the level of take-up was for superfast fixed broadband in each parliamentary constituency in the latest year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539768","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-21","<p>Part of our support to the political process in Libya has included the provision of military advisers and RAF flights to transport them. I am withholding information on the details of these flights as disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-21T15:15:19.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539768/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539768/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Libya: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many RAF flights over Libya have taken place each month between January and June 2016; what the purpose was of such flights; and what the type of aircraft used was for those flights.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539769","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Coalition is in the process of developing a joint policy on investigating civilian casualties. However, until that is finalised, the current policy is that each coalition member investigates civilian casualties according to their respective national methodology.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-26T15:16:23.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539769/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539769/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his oral contribution of the Minister for Armed Forces of 27 June 2016, Official Report, column 19, what recent steps he has taken to develop joint policy on investigating civilian casualties.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","43260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539770","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>As set out in my right hon. Friend the Defence Secretary's contribution, the Ministry of Defence conducts a battle damage assessment after every RAF strike. This assessment reviews the strike, including whether it resulted in civilian casualties. Based on this careful assessment we have no evidence of civilian casualties as a result of any UK strikes in Iraq or Syria since combat operations began in 2014 and 2015 respectively.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-26T15:13:03.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539770/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539770/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his oral contribution of 24 May 2016, Official Report, column 414, whether the battle damage assessment carried out after every RAF strike assesses whether civilians have been injured as a result of UK strikes.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","43259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539771","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence takes its responsibilities to the general public very seriously indeed and would prefer not to cause any disturbance to the general public, including to those in Hull. However, there are no uninhabited areas of the UK large enough to cater for essential training needs.</p><p>Flying operations in the UK Military Low Flying System are avoided within major built-up areas (generally those with a population of over 10,000), although it is not always possible to avoid flying over the outskirts of towns and villages. A range of measures are in place to provide a balance between military training requirements and the need to avoid excessive noise on the ground. These include restrictions placed on the height, speeds and operating procedures of military aircraft in the UK Military Low Flying System.</p><p>Realistic training at night is essential to ensure aircrew are proficient in the necessary skills and to exploit our technological edge. The amount of night low flying remains proportional to the operational requirement.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","43214","2016-07-21T15:17:31.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539771/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539771/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Military Aircraft: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what procedures his Department has to minimise the (a) number of military flights over urban areas and (b) noise pollution such flights cause.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539772","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>An independent Service Police investigation would be triggered in Iraq or Syria when there is substantive evidence that civilians have or may have been killed or injured through the actions of UK forces.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-07-26T15:15:16.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539772/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539772/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39927, what the procedure is for triggering an independent service police investigation into an allegation of civilian casualties.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","43258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539773","Department for Education","false","2016-07-25","<p>The number of pupils attending schools in Bury St Edmunds and known to be eligible for and claiming free school meals in each of the last six years is given in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Pupils on Roll</p></td><td><p>Number of pupils known to be eligible for and claiming FSM</p></td><td><p>% of pupils known to be eligible for and claiming FSM</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2011</p></td><td><p>17,436</p></td><td><p>1,328</p></td><td><p>7.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2012</p></td><td><p>17,412</p></td><td><p>1,365</p></td><td><p>7.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2013</p></td><td><p>17,270</p></td><td><p>1,515</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p>17,294</p></td><td><p>1,716</p></td><td><p>9.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2015</p></td><td><p>17,510</p></td><td><p>1,618</p></td><td><p>9.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2016</p></td><td><p>17,360</p></td><td><p>1,508</p></td><td><p>8.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>This information has been calculated from the underlying data of the ‘schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release[1] for each corresponding year.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-25T15:02:42.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539773/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539773/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Free School Meals: Bury St Edmunds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children living in Bury St Edmunds constituency have been eligible to receive free school meals in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539774","Department for Education","false","2016-07-27","<p>The number of pupils in key stage one classes of more than 30 pupils for each of the years and locations requested is given below, along with the corresponding number of classes:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Bury St Edmunds Constituency</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Suffolk Local Authority</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>East of England</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>Number of Pupils</p></td><td><p>Number of Classes</p></td><td><p>Number of Pupils</p></td><td><p>Number of Classes</p></td><td><p>Number of Pupils</p></td><td><p>Number of Classes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-11</p></td><td><p>157</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>468</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>3,735</p></td><td><p>119</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-12</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>408</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>4,905</p></td><td><p>157</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-13</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>529</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>6,575</p></td><td><p>211</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-14</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>437</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>7,705</p></td><td><p>247</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-15</p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>751</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>9,338</p></td><td><p>299</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-16</p></td><td><p>155</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>716</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>9,451</p></td><td><p>303</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>This information has been taken from the Local authority tables and underlying data of the ‘schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release[1] for the corresponding year.</p><p>Of those infant classes with more than 30 pupils, roughly 95% of pupils are in classes of 31 or 32 pupils and larger classes are uncommon.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-27T09:53:28.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539774/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539774/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Class Sizes: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Key Stage 1 children in (a) Bury St Edmunds constituency, (b) Suffolk and (c) the East of England were in classes of more than 30 children in the academic year beginning September (i) 2010, (ii) 2011, (iii) 2012, (iv) 2013, (iv) 2014 and (v) 2015.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539775","Department for Education","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Department has worked with the Future Leaders Trust to successfully pilot the Executive Educators programme for Multi-Academy Trust (MAT) leaders, which is now being rolled out. The Department is now working closely with a number of leading business schools and higher education providers to ensure that the distinctive programmes which they will each be offering are designed to meet the range of needs amongst current and future MAT leaders.</p><p>The programmes will focus, through a tailored approach, on enabling participants to acquire the business and management skills needed to run and grow a MAT sustainably and effectively. Indicative topics may include: vision-setting and developing strategic capability, governance, financial analysis, commercial awareness and working effectively in partnerships.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-07-25T11:55:20.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539775/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539775/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2016 to Question 42232, what the content of the MAT CEO programme is; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","43274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539776","Department for Education","false","2016-07-27","<p>Of the schools in the North West with a known status, over 80% remained open or partially open to students.</p><p> </p><p>The Department cannot release this information at local authority (LA) level, or the number of teachers who went on strike as this data is provided voluntarily by LAs on the understanding that it will not be published.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-27T13:52:02.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539776/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539776/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Teachers: Strikes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teachers went on strike in Lancashire on 5 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","43270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539777","Department for Education","false","2016-07-21","<p>Performance data for all maintained schools, including academies, is published on the school performance tables website[1]. This provides information that local communities and parents can use to hold schools to account.</p><p>Academies are also subject to independent inspection by Ofsted, which provides an important source of information for local communities and parents.</p><p>The Education white paper, ‘Educational Excellence Everywhere’, set out the Government’s plans to publish performance information for multi-academy trusts in addition to the continued publication of performance data at individual school level. On Thursday 7 July, we published a statistical working paper[2], using our developing approach, showing the performance of multi-academy trusts at Key Stage 2 and Key Stage 4 using 2015 results.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535604/SFR32_2016_text.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535604/SFR32_2016_text.pdf</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-21T08:53:34.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539777/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539777/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Academies: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she has taken to ensure the accountability of academies to their local community; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","43237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539778","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-07-21","<p>We do not hold such information. Reports of dog attacks on people will be held by the Lancashire police force. However, the table below provides information on numbers of prosecutions and convictions for each of the last five years where figures are available, which provides some indication of the number of such incidents.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts and found guilty at all courts of all offences under the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991, Lancashire, 2010 to 2014 <sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Outcome</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proceeded against</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Found guilty</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(1) The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p> </p><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p><p> </p><p>NB: This table reflects cases where the initial proceeding took place in a magistrates court in Lancashire, irrespective of where the offence or arrest occurred, or where any subsequent Crown Court hearing took place.</p><p> </p><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-07-21T16:36:47.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539778/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539778/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-18","Dangerous Dogs: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many attacks on humans by dangerous dogs have been reported in Lancashire in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","43271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539779","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>The UK Government has not made any recent representations to the Government of India on the Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act (AFSPA) or on Indian military intervention in Kashmir. We are aware of the concerns regarding allegations of immunity from prosecution for Indian armed forces personnel under the AFSPA. We continue to follow developments on this issue. The Indian Government have an established mechanism though which people can request that cases of concern be investigated. In November 2015, Indian Prime Minister Modi assured the former Prime Minister, my Rt hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) of his commitment to and respect for India’s core values of tolerance and freedom.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-07-21T15:58:54.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539779/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539779/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Kashmir: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations the Government is making to the government of Indian on the Indian Armed Forces (Jammu and Kashmir) Special Powers Act 1990 and scrutiny of Indian military intervention in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","43275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539780","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>I was deeply saddened by reports of unrest in Kashmir earlier this month and offer my condolences to the victims and their families. Our High Commission in Delhi is monitoring the situation closely and we have updated our travel advice. We have not made any representations to the government of India on this issue.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-07-21T16:00:52.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539780/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539780/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Indian government on civilians killed and injured in Kashmir since the death of Burhan Wani.","false","Biography information for Naz Shah","Bradford West","Naz Shah","43267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539781","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Government has three priorities for the UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants:</p><p>- tackling forced displacement, including through conflict prevention and reduction, and safeguarding human rights and protecting civilians</p><p>- shared global responsibility for the protection of refugees, as well as for regular, safe, and orderly migration and control of irregular migration; and <br>- encouraging controlled, regular migration that has significant development benefits.</p><p>We are finalising details of the UK delegation, including plans for ministerial attendance.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-08-02T15:23:01.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539781/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539781/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539781/answer/previousversion/7957","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many delegates and from which Departments the UK plans to send to the UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539782","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Government has three priorities for the UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants:</p><p>- tackling forced displacement, including through conflict prevention and reduction, and safeguarding human rights and protecting civilians</p><p>- shared global responsibility for the protection of refugees, as well as for regular, safe, and orderly migration and control of irregular migration; and <br>- encouraging controlled, regular migration that has significant development benefits.</p><p>We are finalising details of the UK delegation, including plans for ministerial attendance.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-08-02T15:33:14.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539782/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539782/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539782/answer/previousversion/7960","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his objectives are for the upcoming UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539783","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Government has three priorities for the UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants:</p><p>- tackling forced displacement, including through conflict prevention and reduction, and safeguarding human rights and protecting civilians</p><p>- shared global responsibility for the protection of refugees, as well as for regular, safe, and orderly migration and control of irregular migration; and <br>- encouraging controlled, regular migration that has significant development benefits.</p><p>We are finalising details of the UK delegation, including plans for ministerial attendance.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-08-02T15:38:47.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539783/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539783/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539783/answer/previousversion/7961","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will attend the UNGA Summit on Refugees and Migrants.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539784","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Government remains closely engaged with events in Turkey. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) spoke to President Erdogan on 18 July; the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) spoke to Foreign Minister Cavusoglu on 16 July; and I visited Turkey on 20 and 21 July and met with the Prime Minister, Foreign Minister and others. We continue to receive regular reports from HM Ambassador in Ankara and Embassy officials.</p><p> </p><p>We condemn the attempted coup. We call for the full observance of Turkey’s constitution and stress the importance of the rule of law prevailing in the wake of this failed coup.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to consider the policy implications of developments in Turkey as the situation there evolves.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-08-02T12:59:24.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539784/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539784/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Turkey: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports his Department has received on events in Turkey; and what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the coup attempt in that country on the stability of the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","43293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539785","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>There are currently no national plans in place to change the existing funding system for higher education training in clinical psychology.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T14:40:19.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539785/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539785/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Clinical Psychologists: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to require clinical psychologists to contribute to their training costs either through (a) direct payment and (b) reduction in salary; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","43299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539786","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not keep records of the average time taken to process such refunds. HMRC only holds records for the number of NHS trainees receiving refunds under the widening access scheme from April 2013. A total of 8209 refunds have been processed since then, as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>252</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>4100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2742</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","43281","2016-07-26T07:54:15.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539786/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539786/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average time taken is for refunds on overpaid national insurance and income tax to be paid to NHS trainees under the Widening Access fund.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","43280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539787","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not keep records of the average time taken to process such refunds. HMRC only holds records for the number of NHS trainees receiving refunds under the widening access scheme from April 2013. A total of 8209 refunds have been processed since then, as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>252</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>4100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2742</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","43280","2016-07-26T07:54:18.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539787/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539787/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many NHS trainees under the Widening Access fund received a refund for their overpaid (a) national insurance and (b) income tax contributions in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","43281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539788","Department of Health","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Handbook to the NHS Constitution contains a pledge that 85% of patients have a maximum two month (62-day) wait from urgent referral for suspected cancer to first treatment for all cancers.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested is in the table below:</p><p> </p><p>Percentage of patients in England and Bury St Edmunds constituency<sup>1</sup> that waited 62 days from a general practitioner urgent referral to a first treatment for cancer, 2014-15 and 2015-16</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>NHS Ipswich and East Suffolk CCG</p></td><td><p>NHS West Suffolk CCG</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>83.4%</p></td><td><p>85.8%</p></td><td><p>84.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>82.4%</p></td><td><p>85.2%</p></td><td><p>83.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: </em>Cancer waiting times, NHS England</p><p>Notes:</p><p><sup>1</sup> Bury St Edmunds constituency has two clinical commissioning groups (CCG):</p><p>NHS Ipswich and East Suffolk CCG</p><p>NHS West Suffolk CCG</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-20T16:54:31.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539788/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539788/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of cancer patients in (a) England and (b) Bury St Edmunds constituency received their first cancer treatment within 62 days of an urgent GP referral in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","43252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539789","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>There have been no recent breaches of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 or the Data Protection Act 1998 in relation to the identification of people making requests on the Department’s website. Guidance and training on the Freedom of Information Act 2000 and the Data Protection Act 1998 is provided to Departmental staff on a rolling basis.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-26T15:15:05.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539789/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539789/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that there are no further breaches of Freedom of Information regulations on the identification of people making requests on his Department's website.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","43241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539790","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>Information on the remuneration of chairs is held by individual clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and not collected centrally. West Lancashire CCG has published its chair’s level of remuneration in its Annual Report and Accounts which can be found online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.westlancashireccg.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/AnnualReport_2016_v11.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.westlancashireccg.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/AnnualReport_2016_v11.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>No such assessment has been made by the Department. NHS England has a statutory duty to conduct an annual performance assessment of each CCG. For 2015/16 and previous years it did this through an assurance process. For 2016/17 NHS England has introduced a CCG improvement and assessment framework which supersedes the assurance process. The new system is aligned to delivery of the Five Year Forward View, NHS Planning Guidance and Sustainability and Transformation Plans for each area.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-07-21T08:18:23.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539790/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539790/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","West Lancashire Clinical Commissioning Group: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the level of remuneration was for the chair of NHS West Lancashire Clinical Commissioning  Group in 2015-16; and what assessment he has made of his performance in that role.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","43242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539791","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>Obesity is commonly presented as prevalence. The most recent data available from the Active People Survey shows that between 2012 and 2014 24.0% of adults in Lancashire were obese. This is the same as the average for England.</p><p> </p><p>Data from the National Child Measurement Programme show that for the academic year 2014/15 in Lancashire 9.4% of children in Reception aged 4-5 years were obese; similar to the English average (9.1%). For children aged 10-11 year in Year 6, 18.4% were obese; similar to the value for England (19.1%). Data for 2015/16 is not available.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-07-21T14:33:24.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539791/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539791/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Obesity: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the obesity rate is in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","43268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539792","Department of Health","false","2016-07-21","<p>Chairs that are either employed directly by the clinical commissioning group or are general practitioners performing that role on a fee basis alongside their National Health Service practice duties can participate in the NHS Pension Scheme. As the employer, the clinical commissioning group contributes towards the cost of an individual’s pension benefits. The value of pension related benefit payments made each year in respect of their chairs is recorded by clinical commissioning groups in their annual report. The level of pension benefits that are payable to an individual upon retirement varies based on length of NHS service and will be calculated in accordance with the accrual rate and rules of the relevant pension scheme.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-07-21T13:05:08.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539792/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539792/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what level of pension benefit payments has been awarded to each part-time chair of clinical commissioning group governing bodies in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","43277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539793","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-21","<p><strong></strong>In England and Wales, euthanasia constitutes murder at common law (unless a partial defence applies to reduce the offence to manslaughter); and under section 2(1) of the Suicide Act 1961 it is an offence to do an act capable of encouraging or assisting the suicide or attempted suicide of another person, with the intention so to encourage or assist. Because euthanasia is illegal, the issue of a right to refuse euthanasia does not arise.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-21T14:11:08.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539793/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539793/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-18","Euthanasia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her policy of the Belgian court ruling that a nursing home did not have the right to refuse euthanasia on the grounds of conscientious objection.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","43278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539794","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Government has repeatedly stated that there will be no immediate changes in the circumstances of European nationals and their family members entering or currently residing in the UK. We have published guidance on gov.uk which makes this clear.</p><p>The Government want to be able to guarantee the legal status of EU nationals who are living in the UK, and we are confident that we will be able to do this. But we must also win the same rights for British nationals living in European countries, and it will be a priority for the Government to achieve those things together.</p><p>As part of this process, the Home Secretary will continue to work closely with colleagues across Whitehall and the Government will engage with relevant stakeholders.</p><p>Article 70 of the Vienna Convention applies to States only. It does not create rights for individuals. Nevertheless, we would expect to deal with the rights of EU nationals already living in the UK and the rights of UK citizens living in other EU member states as part of the UK’s exit negotiations.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","43286 ; 43295 ; 43296 ; 43298","2016-07-26T15:09:03.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539794/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539794/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that her Department consults with civil society organisations on the future of EU citizens in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","43288"
