re than one sentence over the period. Only multiple recalls from the same sentence are counted here.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","42807 ; 42810","2016-07-22T13:33:37.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536507/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536507/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Reoffenders: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women supervised by community rehabilitation companies following a prison sentence of less than 12 months have been recalled to prison during their licence period (a) once, (b) twice, (c) three times, (d) four times and (e) five or more times.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","42811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536508","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question in the time allowed. I will write to the honourable member in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-22T12:02:26.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536508/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536508/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many breach proceedings initiated by community rehabilitation companies, the National Probation Service has rejected; and what the reasons for those rejections were.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","42812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536509","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>There is a requirement that home/parent establishments maintain records of all official duties carried out by members of staff, both those duties within their home/parent establishment and within or for any other establishment.</p><p>Establishments are also required to maintain records when members of staff from other establishments carryout duties within or for their establishment.</p><p>Individual members of staff have a responsibility to support the above and are required inform their parent establishment of their wish/intention to work additional hours at another establishment, in advance of the hours being worked. In all circumstances records should be maintained.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-22T13:19:33.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536509/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536509/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Prison Officers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information her Department holds on the number of prison officers who work additional shifts at other prison establishments; and whether line managers at those prison officers' main place of work are aware of additional shifts worked elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","42814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536510","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>Following an audit of the arrangements under which members of staff undertake additional hours/shifts, new arrangements and requirements were introduced that mandated the need to maintain records of all attendance arrangements, both those within parent establishments and also any additional attendance within other establishments.</p><p>The above new arrangements were introduced in 2014 with the publication of Notice to Staff 43/2014.</p><p>Concerns have previously been raised relating to staff undertaking additional hours/shifts within establishments other than their home/parent establishment by the Prison Officers Association. It is felt that the introduction of the above address’s this, as the arrangements ensure that information is readily available to managers to enable them to monitor the additional attendance.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-22T11:51:57.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536510/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536510/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Prison Officers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what representations she has received on prison officers working additional shifts in other prison establishments than those at which they are based without the knowledge of their line management.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","42815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536511","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>We will set out our proposals for a Bill of Rights in due course. We will fully consult on our proposals.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-19T15:58:07.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536511/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536511/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Human Rights Act 1998","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has for reform of the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","42839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536512","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>We expect to announce the conclusion of the review of Employment Tribunals fees in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-19T16:15:58.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536512/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536512/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when her Department plans to publish its review of employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","42840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536513","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-19","<p>The government remains clear that judicial review, when used properly, is a crucial component of the rule of law.</p><p> </p><p>But too often the system is open to abuse, and that is why we have taken forward reform. These changes include creating the Planning Court, in which significant challenges are considered by judges with planning expertise to time targets, and sections of the Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015, such as allowing appeals of national significance to more often move direct to the Supreme Court, reducing the potential for delay.</p><p> </p><p>A number of the outstanding reforms will take effect in due course, and the government is currently seeking further views on proposals for providing the courts with information on how judicial review applications are being funded.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-07-19T15:45:53.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536513/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536513/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Judicial Review: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has for reform of judicial review.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","42838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536514","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-22","<p>The National Probation Service does not authorise recall requests on behalf of the Secretary of State. Therefore, we have interpreted your question relating to breach proceedings in relation to those cases where a Community Rehabilitation Company is seeking an endorsement of a recall request by the National Probation Service before it is submitted for authorisation. This applies to cases where there is evidence of an increase in the offender’s risk of serious harm to high and the risk is not deemed to be imminent. We do not hold this information centrally and, therefore, it is not possible to provide you with the information which you have requested.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-07-22T13:39:30.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536514/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536514/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-14","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of breach proceedings initiated by community rehabilitation companies resulted in a person being recalled to prison by the National Probation Service in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","42813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536515","Scotland Office","false","2016-07-19","<p>Details of meetings with external organisations are published in quarterly returns which are available at gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-07-19T10:01:00.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536515/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536515/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-07-14","Trade Unions: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many meetings he has had in the last six months with (a) Scottish Trades Union Congress and (b) affiliated trade unions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","42790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536516","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>Performance benchmarks were set for the entire Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise, not by constituent business groups, e.g. Southern. Since Rail Industry period 7 in financial year 2015/16 (ending mid October 2015), GTR exceeded the breach level for the Cancellations benchmark. Last year the then Secretary of State issued GTR with a Remedial Plan Notice requiring them to set out the measures they will take in order to improve their performance. The then Secretary of State has published the Remedial Plan and it includes benchmarks against which GTR are measured for the duration of the Plan.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-07-21T08:52:31.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536516/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536516/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-14","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, in which reporting periods Southern Railway's performance met the specified benchmarks set out in the franchise agreement since that agreement was signed.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","42865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536517","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-18","<p>We will begin the process of updating the Cycle to Work Scheme guidance published on GOV.UK and engage with Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) over the summer. We will then have a firmer view on the timescales involved for review and any changes to be made. This will include any decision made on the maximum allowance.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-07-18T14:18:24.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536517/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536517/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-14","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2016 to Question 42538, what the timescale is for updating the Cycle to Work scheme guidance published on gov.uk; and when he expects to reach a decision on the maximum allowance for disabled cyclists.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","42866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536518","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>The current number of people that receive their benefit or pension payments by Simple Payment in the Liverpool City Region is 1,399.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-07-19T11:44:37.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536518/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536518/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Social Security Benefits: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people receive benefit and pension payments by Simple Payments in the Liverpool City Region.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","42870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536519","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>As the Minister with the responsibility for health and safety, the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) is focused on improving health outcomes in the food industry by working with stakeholders to implement a five year food manufacturing national strategy (2016-21) and this includes reducing cases of occupational asthma in bakeries and allied premises.</p><p>HSE is also inspecting bakeries and allied food manufacturing premises to determine how effectively worker exposure to flour dust is controlled.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-19T11:29:28.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536519/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536519/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Bakeries: Asthma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what advice and guidance he has received from the Health and Safety Executive on reducing the level of occupational asthma in the baking industry.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","42856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536520","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-22","<p>Motability is an independent charitable organisation wholly responsible for the Motability scheme. It is therefore Motability’s decision whether to allow claimants to keep their vehicle during this period.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants are allowed to keep their vehicle for up to seven weeks following a decision that they are no longer entitled to PIP, with Mandatory Reconsiderations normally completed well before this. Most are also eligible for a £2,000 transitional support payment. Those who win their appeal can normally reapply for the scheme immediately, providing they repay this; otherwise, they can re-join after 6 months.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-22T12:12:17.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536520/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536520/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason Motability is required to repossess a claimant's vehicle before mandatory reconsideration or appeals related to personal independent payment claim applications.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","42852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536521","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>Since the inception of the Vaccine Damage Payment Scheme, 4236 claims have been made where whooping cough is amongst the vaccines cited on the claim form. Of those, 710 resulted in an award. The figures include claims where whooping cough was administered as a single vaccination or as part of a combined vaccine e.g. DTaP/IPV (Diphtheria, Tetanus, Pertussis/Whooping Cough and Polio). As previously advised it is not possible to state how many, if any, of the claims listed above were made specifically in relation to whooping cough.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-07-19T15:54:20.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536521/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536521/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Whooping Cough: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2016 to Question 42446, how many people have (a) claimed and (b) received payment under the vaccine damages payment scheme where one of the vaccines cited in the claim was one used for whooping cough.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","42829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536522","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>The Government regularly assesses the impacts of its policies and will continue to do so.</p><p>The Government’s economic plan is delivering jobs for the UK. Our reforms, including the introduction of the National Living Wage, are helping to transform the life chances of people across the country.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-19T16:30:32.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536522/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536522/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the recommendations concerning austerity measures in paragraph 19 of the UN Economic and Social Council report entitled, Concluding observations on the sixth periodic report of the United Kingdom and Great Britain and Northern Ireland, published on 24 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","42786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536523","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>The Work Programme prime providers that cover Glasgow are Ingeus and Working Links. They have complete freedom to innovate and design support based on individual and local need. That support can take many forms, including learning new skills, work experience and developing job hunting techniques. As prime providers they have the freedom to use a network of local specialist organisations to deliver tailored support to the individual.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-19T11:00:33.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536523/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536523/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Work Programme: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which companies are currently participating in the Work Programme in Glasgow; and what work experience each of those companies offers to benefit claimants.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","42789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536524","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-19","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>Information on Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions, by cumulative frequency and geography, is available here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-07-19T11:09:13.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536524/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536524/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Social Security Benefits: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants were sanctioned more than once in (a) Glasgow South West constituency and (b) Glasgow in (i) 2011-12, (ii) 2012-13, (iii) 2013-14, (iv) 2014-15 and (v) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","42788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536532","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>Highways England is responsible for maintaining the road traffic signs on the Strategic Road Network (SRN). This duty is discharged through contractors who maintain the signs in accordance with Highways England standards.</p><p> </p><p>Any defects can be reported via the Highways England Customer Contact Centre <a href="mailto:info@highwaysengland.co.uk" target="_blank">info@highwaysengland.co.uk</a> or by telephone on 0300 123 5000.</p><p>Local highway authorities have a duty under Section 41 of the Highways Act 1980 to maintain the highways network, including traffic signs, in their area.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport encourages local highway authorities to provide facilities, through their websites or mobile phone apps, for members of the public to report defects on the highway they are responsible for.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-21T13:41:54.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536532/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536532/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-14","Road Signs and Markings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who is responsible for ensuring that road signs on Highways England and local authority roads are visible, clean and not obscured by foliage; and how members of the public can report signs that fail to meet those standards.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536533","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>Information on whether an apprenticeship is undertaken by a single parent is not centrally collected.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows apprenticeship starts by gender, 2010/11 to 2014/15:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Female</strong></p></td><td><p>245,990</p></td><td><p>53.8%</p></td><td><p>276,220</p></td><td><p>53.1%</p></td><td><p>279,000</p></td><td><p>54.7%</p></td><td><p>232,940</p></td><td><p>52.9%</p></td><td><p>264,750</p></td><td><p>53.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Male</strong></p></td><td><p>211,220</p></td><td><p>46.2%</p></td><td><p>244,360</p></td><td><p>46.9%</p></td><td><p>231,210</p></td><td><p>45.3%</p></td><td><p>207,480</p></td><td><p>47.1%</p></td><td><p>235,140</p></td><td><p>47.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>457,200</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td><td><p>520,600</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td><td><p>510,200</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td><td><p>440,400</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td><td><p>499,900</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:20:58.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536533/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536533/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-14","Apprentices: Lone Parents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) female, and (2) male, single parents have (a) started, and (b) completed, apprenticeships in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL1207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536534","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>Information on whether an apprenticeship has been advertised as part time is not collected centrally. Apprenticeships can be advertised in many ways, including on the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are full-time jobs; therefore an apprentice should work at least 30 hours per week. In exceptional circumstances, such as where the apprentice has caring responsibilities, a minimum of 16 hours per week may be agreed between the apprentice and the employer. In circumstances where the apprentice works fewer than 30 hours per week, the duration of the apprenticeship must be extended in proportion so that the minimum duration requirements are still met.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:23:06.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536534/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536534/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-14","Apprentices: Part-time Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many apprenticeship placements have been advertised as part-time in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL1208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536535","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-28","<p>Estimates for the numbers of female and male single parents who earn less than the median average income are shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Millions, 2014/15, United Kingdom</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Below 2014/15 median household income</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of female Lone Parents in work:</p></td><td><p><strong>0.8</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of male Lone Parents in work:</p></td><td><p><strong>0.1</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Average income is defined as the median equivalised net household income, where median income divides the population of individuals, when ranked by income, into two equal sized groups.</p><p>These statistics are based on Households Below Average Income analysis.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-07-28T14:01:10.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536535/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536535/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-14","Lone Parents: Low Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) female, and (2) male, single parents earn less than the median average income.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL1209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536536","Department for Education","false","2016-07-25","<p>Parents on apprenticeships with three- and four-year-olds are eligible for 30 hours of free childcare under the Childcare Act 2016 in the same way as other working households. They will need to be earning the equivalent of 16 hours work per week at the apprentice national minimum wage rate.</p><p> </p><p>The national minimum wage rates are set out at the GOV.UK website.</p><p> </p><p>Apprentices will need to meet the other eligibility criteria in addition to the minimum earnings requirement in order to qualify. The key eligibility criteria are set out in a policy statement issued in December 2015, which is attached to this answer.</p><p>We will set out the eligibility criteria in more detail in forthcoming regulations, and these will be subject to affirmative debates in both Houses.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-25T12:26:33.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536536/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536536/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-14","Children: Day Care","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to enable those on apprenticeships to claim 30 hours of free childcare under the Childcare Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL1210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536537","Home Office","false","2016-07-28","<p>As of 15th July 2016 there were over 19 million custody images, which may include images other than of faces, uploaded by forces onto the PND. Of these, 16,644,143 had been enrolled in the facial image recognition gallery and are searchable using automated facial recognition software.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-28T15:50:06.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536537/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536537/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-14","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many facial images are held on the Police National Database.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL1211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536538","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>Since 22nd June 2012 - 12 million custody images, which may include images other than of faces, have been uploaded by forces onto the PND. Of these, as of 15th July 2016 - 9,941,293 have been enrolled in the facial image recognition gallery and are searchable using automated facial recognition software.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:22:43.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536538/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536538/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-14","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many facial images have been added to the Police National Database since the High Court ruling in the case of <i>R (RMC and FJ) v MPS</i> [2012] EWHC 1681(Admin).","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL1212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536539","Home Office","false","2016-07-28","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-28T14:54:45.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536539/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536539/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-14","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many facial images held on the Police National Database are of individuals who have not been charged with an offence.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL1213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536540","Home Office","false","2016-07-28","<p>The Review on the Use and Retention of Custody Images will examine the current legal and operational framework governing custody images, including the Human Rights Act 1998. This Review will be published in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-28T15:14:41.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536540/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/536540/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-14","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how the present system of up-loading, storage and searching of facial images on the Police National Database complies with the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL1214"
